1
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:15,000
Subtitle by Mr_Qwerty

2
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:23,074
Delicious Vegan Sausages, Cheese
and Burgers - Vegusto.co.uk

3
00:00:49,790 --> 00:00:52,390
(HE SIGHS)

4
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:01,430
(SILENCE)

5
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:04,630
(CLOCK CHIMES)

6
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:37,350
St Merryn's Hospital, Wednesday May 12th.

7
00:01:38,960 --> 00:01:41,950
Or is it still Tuesday May 11th?

8
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:45,710
No...

9
00:01:45,880 --> 00:01:50,550
It must be Wednesday because most of the time
the noise of the traffic is so loud

10
00:01:50,720 --> 00:01:54,150
that you need earplugs to hear yourself think.

11
00:01:54,320 --> 00:01:57,510
It must be Wednesday because most of the time
the noise of the traffic is so loud

12
00:01:57,680 --> 00:02:01,870
that means it must be the silent early hours.

13
00:02:03,320 --> 00:02:05,990
Three, four, who knows?

14
00:02:08,520 --> 00:02:10,790
But I'm already awake.

15
00:02:12,160 --> 00:02:15,830
What's more, I'm hungry. Isn't it ridiculous?

16
00:02:18,320 --> 00:02:21,590
The nurses come in at seven, on the dot.

17
00:02:22,600 --> 00:02:25,160
With a lovely cup of tea.

18
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:28,230
Then the wash, then the breakfast.

19
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:32,100
And then today - great day...

20
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:35,990
Eureka.

21
00:02:36,920 --> 00:02:39,510
These bandages come off.

22
00:02:42,120 --> 00:02:43,870
Roll on...

23
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:47,670
Roll on seven o'clock.

24
00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:53,950
So...

25
00:02:55,400 --> 00:02:59,230
I'm taking the opportunity of this waiting time

26
00:02:59,400 --> 00:03:01,990
to reply to your cassette.

27
00:03:02,680 --> 00:03:06,350
Dear Walter, many thanks for your cassette.

28
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:09,630
There we are.

29
00:03:14,440 --> 00:03:18,910
I've been doing a lot of thinking
while I've been lying here, Wal.

30
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:21,710
And I've come to a decision.

31
00:03:21,880 --> 00:03:26,740
I've had enough. I'm chucking the job.
I'm fed up with triffids.

32
00:03:27,760 --> 00:03:30,110
I wanna be loved.

33
00:03:30,280 --> 00:03:34,030
I wanna breed puppies and plant potatoes.

34
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:38,750
So, as you are gonna write your book about triffs,

35
00:03:38,920 --> 00:03:42,790
and on condition that
I never have to mention them again,

36
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:45,420
I'll use this waiting time.

37
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:50,950
It's not that I'm worried about this morning.

38
00:03:52,040 --> 00:03:54,420
It's just that I'm scared stiff!

39
00:03:56,040 --> 00:03:58,790
I'll use this time to do as you ask

40
00:03:58,960 --> 00:04:01,790
and give you some of my theories
about the early days.

41
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:03,950
Some of it's more than theories, too.

42
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:08,950
<i>The stories about Palanguez
I got from a good source.</i>

43
00:04:09,120 --> 00:04:13,110
<i>In 1961 he turned up
at the office of European Oils.</i>

44
00:04:13,280 --> 00:04:18,190
<i>We've had it analysed, Mr Palanguez.
Experts confirm it is a vegetable oil.</i>

45
00:04:18,360 --> 00:04:22,630
- But with extraordinary properties.
- I've never seen anything like it.

46
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:25,830
You'll see a great deal of it, Mr Grant.

47
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,870
It will come on the market in seven or eight years.

48
00:04:30,040 --> 00:04:33,870
<i>- Possibly.
- As an additive to petroleum?</i>

49
00:04:34,040 --> 00:04:38,030
- Yes.
- With an energy saving of over 30%?

50
00:04:39,520 --> 00:04:43,590
<i>Do you intend to market it yourself,
Mr Palanguez?</i>

51
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:47,300
Would I be showing it to you if I did?

52
00:04:47,480 --> 00:04:50,710
I suppose you have a proposition.
Shall we come to it?

53
00:04:50,880 --> 00:04:55,430
The plant from which this oil is obtained
is a completely new species.

54
00:04:55,600 --> 00:04:59,270
I might be able to provide the seeds of this plant.

55
00:04:59,440 --> 00:05:02,350
If you commence cultivation at once,

56
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:08,150
you could begin production of the oil in five years,
or it might be six for full yield.

57
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:11,270
You would still be in advance of your competitors.

58
00:05:11,440 --> 00:05:16,630
Or I could always come to an arrangement
with the competitors.

59
00:05:16,800 --> 00:05:21,550
I think you will find they are not
approachable - or suppressible.

60
00:05:21,720 --> 00:05:25,110
You mean they're behind the Iron Curtain?

61
00:05:26,960 --> 00:05:28,950
Seeds, you said.

62
00:05:29,120 --> 00:05:33,390
Have you heard of a Russian professor
of biology called Lysenko?

63
00:05:33,560 --> 00:05:36,470
There are rumours he's made
some strange experiments.

64
00:05:36,640 --> 00:05:38,940
I have heard these rumours.

65
00:05:39,120 --> 00:05:42,740
What figure did you have in mind
for getting us the seeds?

66
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:45,430
Ten million pounds.

67
00:05:45,600 --> 00:05:47,230
(GRANT LAUGHS)

68
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:52,190
And a percentage of the profits.
It is a very dangerous business, Mr Grant.

69
00:05:52,360 --> 00:05:54,550
There are many people I must pay.

70
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:59,550
For you, the choice is between ruin
or a monopoly in the Western world.

71
00:05:59,720 --> 00:06:02,180
I will not lower my price.

72
00:06:02,360 --> 00:06:05,790
<i>And he didn't lower it.
And they paid him - or part of it -</i>

73
00:06:05,960 --> 00:06:09,350
<i>because Mr Palanguez was never seen again.</i>

74
00:06:10,520 --> 00:06:15,510
Of course, in the end,
the company got those seeds.

75
00:06:15,680 --> 00:06:20,510
But by the time they did,
they weren't the only ones. What they...

76
00:06:20,680 --> 00:06:23,670
(GLASS SMASHES)

77
00:06:39,160 --> 00:06:41,750
<i>(TAPE REWINDS)</i>

78
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:45,950
<i>(TAPE) By the time they did,
they weren't the only ones. What...</i>

79
00:06:46,120 --> 00:06:49,110
(RECORDED GLASS SMASHING)

80
00:06:51,560 --> 00:06:54,590
Sorry about the sound effects, Wal.

81
00:06:54,760 --> 00:06:58,110
Somewhere in the night a window smashed.

82
00:06:58,280 --> 00:07:01,190
We'll be deafened with police sirens any minute!

83
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:05,630
Meanwhile, back to the triffids.

84
00:07:06,920 --> 00:07:12,710
<i>My first experience of them was when
I still lived at home with Mum and Dad.</i>

85
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:20,310
<i>It was a year or so after Palanguez disappeared,
not that I'd ever heard of him then.</i>

86
00:07:20,480 --> 00:07:25,910
<i>But we know from a Russian
that the seeds had been taken away.</i>

87
00:07:26,080 --> 00:07:31,710
<i>I always thought that Russian fighters
got on his tail and shot him up.</i>

88
00:07:32,640 --> 00:07:38,590
<i>Those seeds are like vapour.
If they got out, they'd drift almost anywhere.</i>

89
00:07:38,760 --> 00:07:42,830
- Funny, isn't it, Dad?
- Yes, it is a little curious.

90
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:45,510
Rather curious.

91
00:07:45,680 --> 00:07:49,300
- Any idea of what it is?
- No, not really.

92
00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:52,230
It's blown in from somewhere.

93
00:07:52,400 --> 00:07:57,030
Either that or a foreign import
of some sort I know not what of.

94
00:07:57,200 --> 00:08:01,270
Or else some new strain
that someone's been rearing.

95
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:04,350
What are these stumps at the bottom?

96
00:08:04,520 --> 00:08:08,060
Search me. Very peculiar.

97
00:08:08,240 --> 00:08:09,830
Here...

98
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:12,990
Come on, Bill. Have a look inside. Come on.

99
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:18,670
- Ugh!
- Come on, Bill, that's nature.

100
00:08:18,840 --> 00:08:21,630
I've grown rather fond of it, myself.

101
00:08:22,200 --> 00:08:25,190
I shall take care of you, old chap.

102
00:08:26,120 --> 00:08:28,150
There's no need to fret.

103
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:31,830
<i>Not long after this,
I went to the cinema with a pal.</i>

104
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:35,910
<i>In those days, they still showed
newsreels before the film.</i>

105
00:08:36,080 --> 00:08:41,070
<i>(NEWSREEL) Get a load of what's going on
in EcuadorI Vegetables on vacationI</i>

106
00:08:41,240 --> 00:08:47,190
<i>You might have seen this after a party,
but in Ecuador they see it any time.</i>

107
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:50,150
<i>Monster plants on the march.</i>

108
00:08:50,320 --> 00:08:53,910
<i>This gives me an idea.
If we educate our potatoes,</i>

109
00:08:54,080 --> 00:08:57,150
<i>we can fix it so they walk straight in the potI</i>

110
00:08:57,320 --> 00:09:00,710
<i>(BILL) They were the same
as the plant in our garden.</i>

111
00:09:00,880 --> 00:09:05,110
<i>I was sure they were. And if they could walk...</i>

112
00:09:14,080 --> 00:09:15,910
<i>(WHIPLASH SOUND )</i>

113
00:09:16,080 --> 00:09:17,950
Aghh!

114
00:09:19,520 --> 00:09:24,510
<i>I was the first person in England
to have been stung by a triffid.</i>

115
00:09:24,680 --> 00:09:28,430
<i>Our plant was too young
for its poison to be fully effective.</i>

116
00:09:28,600 --> 00:09:31,270
<i>The doctors managed to save my life.</i>

117
00:09:33,320 --> 00:09:38,630
<i>We were beginning to learn about the tri-feds,
or triffids as they came to be called.</i>

118
00:09:40,240 --> 00:09:43,940
<i>They couldn't only walk. They could kill.</i>

119
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:48,190
<i>Triffids began to appear all over the world.</i>

120
00:09:48,360 --> 00:09:51,350
<i>Something else about them sickened everyone.</i>

121
00:09:51,520 --> 00:09:54,230
<i>Triffids were also carnivores.</i>

122
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:58,100
<i>They stung their victims,
then waited for the flesh to decompose.</i>

123
00:09:58,280 --> 00:10:01,270
<i>Not until then could they use it for food.</i>

124
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:04,990
<i>Triffids were hacked down by the thousand.</i>

125
00:10:05,160 --> 00:10:08,670
<i>The new plant was
very nearly eliminated from earth.</i>

126
00:10:08,840 --> 00:10:12,230
<i>Very nearly. But not quite.</i>

127
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:15,910
Because scientists realised the nasty triffid

128
00:10:16,080 --> 00:10:19,780
was the same plant from Russia
that produced the wonderful oil.

129
00:10:19,960 --> 00:10:23,740
- Triffids were...
- (CLOCK CHIMES)

130
00:10:23,920 --> 00:10:28,710
That meant that triffids were very lovely
and very big business.

131
00:10:29,360 --> 00:10:34,630
As I had a bond with them, I went to work on
a triffid farm and so did you. You know the rest.

132
00:10:34,800 --> 00:10:38,110
Meanwhile, we'll pause for the time.

133
00:10:40,160 --> 00:10:44,350
(CLOCK CHIMES THE HOUR)

134
00:10:55,120 --> 00:10:59,510
<i>- (CHIMES STOP)
- What the hell's going on? It's eight o'clock!</i>

135
00:10:59,680 --> 00:11:04,700
They should have been in at seven.
They've got to take these bloody bandages off!

136
00:11:11,760 --> 00:11:14,030
I'm sorry about that.

137
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:18,230
You get like a kid when you're as helpless as this.

138
00:11:19,160 --> 00:11:21,720
There must be some emergency on.

139
00:11:21,880 --> 00:11:26,470
There's no point in me getting into a paddy.
There's nothing I could...

140
00:11:28,720 --> 00:11:31,830
That's funny. Where's all the traffic got to?

141
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:37,550
The worst thing about living in this blackness

142
00:11:37,720 --> 00:11:42,310
is that there's no certainty
of knowing anything at all.

143
00:11:42,480 --> 00:11:48,070
For all I know, three nurses and a doctor
are playing blind man's buff with me.

144
00:11:48,240 --> 00:11:53,670
Or they might have moved me somewhere
while I was asleep. I've never seen this room.

145
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,830
Anyway...

146
00:11:59,240 --> 00:12:02,310
there's obviously some explanation.

147
00:12:03,680 --> 00:12:06,670
Apart from the fact I've gone bananas.

148
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:18,390
It reminds me of that conversation
we were having the other week.

149
00:12:18,560 --> 00:12:22,260
<i>Do you remember
when we were talking about triffids?</i>

150
00:12:22,440 --> 00:12:25,390
<i>That evening we were working late.</i>

151
00:12:26,360 --> 00:12:28,870
They can tap number three field tomorrow.

152
00:12:29,040 --> 00:12:30,470
Yep.

153
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:35,950
For now, that's it. I've had enough.

154
00:12:37,120 --> 00:12:39,190
I'm going home.

155
00:12:39,360 --> 00:12:42,550
- Time for walkies.
- Don't you start.

156
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:45,950
- What?
- Kiddy talk about triffs.

157
00:12:46,120 --> 00:12:49,110
Who have you been falling out with?

158
00:12:50,360 --> 00:12:53,470
Jack Richards has planted a triffid in his garden

159
00:12:53,640 --> 00:12:56,350
so his daughter can have it for a pet.

160
00:12:56,520 --> 00:12:58,710
He wouldn't be the first.

161
00:12:58,880 --> 00:13:04,550
<i>Perfectly safe if he keeps it on some sort of chain
and cuts the sting out every two years.</i>

162
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:08,590
- Quite fun for a kid in lots of ways.
- Fun?!

163
00:13:09,560 --> 00:13:12,750
- Have a nightcap?
- Yeah. Ta.

164
00:13:17,200 --> 00:13:19,950
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

165
00:13:21,040 --> 00:13:24,030
We know very little about them, you know.

166
00:13:24,200 --> 00:13:27,630
For example, what do you think that is,

167
00:13:27,800 --> 00:13:30,710
when they rattle their sticks against their stem?

168
00:13:30,880 --> 00:13:35,710
I thought we decided
it was a sort of primitive mating call.

169
00:13:35,880 --> 00:13:38,390
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

170
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:43,790
I think they're talking.

171
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:46,710
Talking?!

172
00:13:46,880 --> 00:13:51,790
I've been thinking that for some time.
Now I'm prepared to say so.

173
00:13:51,960 --> 00:13:54,230
Well, to you, anyway.

174
00:13:54,400 --> 00:13:57,430
Walter, a talking plant is ridiculous!

175
00:13:57,600 --> 00:14:00,060
So is a walking plant, but a triffid walks.

176
00:14:00,240 --> 00:14:04,550
- Well, it moves about.
- That's quibbling. It walks.

177
00:14:04,720 --> 00:14:08,870
And if I'm right and it talks, or communicates,

178
00:14:09,040 --> 00:14:11,710
that means somewhere inside it is intelligence.

179
00:14:11,880 --> 00:14:14,110
We've dissected them. There's no brain.

180
00:14:14,280 --> 00:14:17,470
Something might do a brain's job.

181
00:14:17,640 --> 00:14:21,340
Look at what they attack.
They almost always go for the head.

182
00:14:21,520 --> 00:14:26,510
A great number of people who have been stung
but not killed have been blinded.

183
00:14:26,680 --> 00:14:29,060
- That's significant.
- Of what?

184
00:14:29,240 --> 00:14:32,670
They know the shortest way
of putting a man out of action.

185
00:14:32,840 --> 00:14:37,110
If it were a choice of survival
between a blind man and a triffid,

186
00:14:37,280 --> 00:14:41,350
- I know which I'd put my money on.
- You're assuming equal intelligence.

187
00:14:41,520 --> 00:14:45,470
I'm not. They don't need
their intelligence to equal ours.

188
00:14:45,640 --> 00:14:47,910
What do you mean?

189
00:14:48,080 --> 00:14:50,670
<i>(TAPPING CONTINUES)</i>

190
00:14:55,480 --> 00:14:58,670
Look how complicated it is
for us to feed ourselves.

191
00:14:58,840 --> 00:15:02,380
Even to just grow things and eat them raw.

192
00:15:02,560 --> 00:15:06,830
They live off the soil
or from insects or bits of rotten meat.

193
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:12,950
Look at the complex process
we have to go through to get oil from them.

194
00:15:13,120 --> 00:15:16,790
<i>Put that in reverse.
How would they make use of us?</i>

195
00:15:16,960 --> 00:15:22,950
Give us a sting, wait a few days
and they've got everything they need to live.

196
00:15:23,120 --> 00:15:26,110
That doesn't take very much intelligence.

197
00:15:29,120 --> 00:15:33,350
- You don't like them very much, do you?
- They fascinate me.

198
00:15:33,520 --> 00:15:36,670
I shall write a book about them one day.

199
00:15:36,840 --> 00:15:40,070
If they do have this intelligence,

200
00:15:40,240 --> 00:15:42,510
are you afraid of it?

201
00:15:43,880 --> 00:15:47,230
Why should I be? They're under control.

202
00:15:47,400 --> 00:15:49,960
(WALTER) There's only one thing, though.

203
00:15:50,120 --> 00:15:53,070
I'd like to know what they're nattering about.

204
00:15:54,440 --> 00:15:56,470
- (KNOCKING)
- Come in.

205
00:15:59,080 --> 00:16:02,670
(WOMAN WAILS)

206
00:16:12,800 --> 00:16:15,360
What's going on?!

207
00:16:44,920 --> 00:16:46,510
Hey!

208
00:16:46,680 --> 00:16:51,510
Do you think I could possibly
have some breakfast? Room 22!

209
00:16:51,680 --> 00:16:53,710
(SILENCE)

210
00:17:34,160 --> 00:17:36,590
I think I'm going mad.

211
00:17:36,760 --> 00:17:38,990
I must be.

212
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,350
Or something's happened,
and God only knows what it is.

213
00:17:43,520 --> 00:17:45,820
Oh, Christ!

214
00:17:48,960 --> 00:17:51,950
The sweat's running down my neck.

215
00:17:54,120 --> 00:17:56,990
It's Wednesday May 12th.

216
00:17:57,160 --> 00:18:02,280
Yesterday was May 11th. Only one night's
passed and everything was normal then.

217
00:18:02,440 --> 00:18:07,380
<i>(WOMAN'S VOICE) The sky is just full
of shooting starsI</i>

218
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:10,310
Is it to do with last night?

219
00:18:12,400 --> 00:18:15,470
You saw it, I suppose.

220
00:18:15,640 --> 00:18:18,200
I must have been the only person that didn't.

221
00:18:18,360 --> 00:18:22,590
We've drawn back the curtains in the wards
so the patients can look out.

222
00:18:22,760 --> 00:18:25,630
What did the radio say it was? Comet what?

223
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:27,470
(BILL) Debris.

224
00:18:27,640 --> 00:18:30,390
It's amazing, Mr Mason!

225
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:34,510
Before we get this down my front,
we'd better call it a day.

226
00:18:35,440 --> 00:18:39,310
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- It's all right. I'm only joking.

227
00:18:39,480 --> 00:18:42,070
It's just jealousy, missing all the fun.

228
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:45,230
- Are you sure you've had enough?
- Yes, thank you.

229
00:18:52,640 --> 00:18:55,070
- Evening, Nurse.
- Good evening, Doctor.

230
00:18:55,240 --> 00:19:00,630
Evening, Mr Mason. I'm Doctor Soames.
Your specialist asked me to see you.

231
00:19:00,800 --> 00:19:03,550
Oh. Good evening, Dr Soames.

232
00:19:03,720 --> 00:19:05,750
Will you be needing me, Doctor?

233
00:19:05,920 --> 00:19:08,790
- No, thank you, Nurse.
- Good night, Mr Mason.

234
00:19:08,960 --> 00:19:10,910
Good night, Barbara.

235
00:19:11,080 --> 00:19:14,670
- Enjoy the free show.
- Thank you. I will.

236
00:19:16,760 --> 00:19:20,910
- It's quite something you're missing.
- So I'm told.

237
00:19:22,240 --> 00:19:24,950
I'm sorry. Must be very boring for you.

238
00:19:25,120 --> 00:19:30,910
Mr Carter will see you after breakfast,
but don't be tempted to peep before then.

239
00:19:31,080 --> 00:19:33,950
These things have to be handled carefully.

240
00:19:34,120 --> 00:19:38,590
Exactly the right amount of light...
and that sort of thing,

241
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:44,940
otherwise some very expert work and ten days'
patience could be ruined in a couple of seconds.

242
00:19:45,120 --> 00:19:48,310
- You understand that?
- Yes, of course.

243
00:19:48,480 --> 00:19:51,070
Good. Triffid sting, wasn't it?

244
00:19:52,080 --> 00:19:55,070
Yes, that's right. I work on a triffid farm.

245
00:19:55,240 --> 00:19:57,750
I thought they all had their stings docked.

246
00:19:57,920 --> 00:20:00,550
Not the ones we tap for oil.

247
00:20:00,720 --> 00:20:03,830
The oil's better quality if we don't dock them.

248
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:08,310
I see. You wear some sort of
protective clothing, don't you?

249
00:20:08,480 --> 00:20:14,950
Oh, yes. But some of those stings are
ten feet long. They can catch you at any angle.

250
00:20:15,120 --> 00:20:18,990
This one swiped me on the side of the mask
and the poison got inside.

251
00:20:19,160 --> 00:20:22,190
- You're lucky to be alive, aren't you?
- Yes.

252
00:20:22,360 --> 00:20:26,110
I wouldn't be here if it hadn't been for my friend.

253
00:20:26,280 --> 00:20:29,190
He took me inside and gave me the antidote.

254
00:20:29,360 --> 00:20:32,980
Added to which I must have
built up some resistance.

255
00:20:33,160 --> 00:20:37,870
- That's the second time they got me.
- Haven't you had enough of them?

256
00:20:38,040 --> 00:20:40,420
I've decided - I have!

257
00:20:40,600 --> 00:20:43,430
Well, good luck for tomorrow.

258
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:47,430
I'm going to join the gawpers on the roof.
Good night, Mr Mason.

259
00:20:47,600 --> 00:20:49,870
Good night, Doctor.

260
