471
00:42:01,390 --> 00:42:08,190
<i># So late into the night</i>

472
00:42:09,550 --> 00:42:16,430
<i># Though the heart be ne'er as loving</i>

473
00:42:16,590 --> 00:42:22,700
<i># And the moon be still as bright</i>

474
00:42:24,710 --> 00:42:30,980
<i># Though the heart be ne'er as loving</i>

475
00:42:31,870 --> 00:42:35,420
<i># And the moon... #</i>

476
00:42:38,710 --> 00:42:41,710
<i>(SINGER WEEPS)</i>

477
00:42:52,190 --> 00:42:54,830
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

478
00:42:59,510 --> 00:43:03,220
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

479
00:43:13,790 --> 00:43:17,100
Get off, you bastard! She's mine! I found her.

480
00:43:17,270 --> 00:43:20,150
I'll cut you!

481
00:43:21,390 --> 00:43:23,380
Get out of it!

482
00:43:23,550 --> 00:43:25,990
<i>(BILL) Pull on that hard!</i>

483
00:43:34,910 --> 00:43:36,900
Come on.

484
00:43:45,270 --> 00:43:49,470
<i>- By the way, I'm Bill Mason.
- Josella Payton.</i>

485
00:43:49,630 --> 00:43:53,790
But Josella's a hell of a mouthful, so I'm called Jo.

486
00:43:57,390 --> 00:44:01,430
I take it you didn't see that comet stuff last night.

487
00:44:01,590 --> 00:44:04,030
No. Why?

488
00:44:04,790 --> 00:44:06,670
Well...

489
00:44:06,830 --> 00:44:09,910
that seems to be the main cause of it.

490
00:44:10,070 --> 00:44:14,990
This comet was so bright,
it burned out something in the eye.

491
00:44:16,270 --> 00:44:19,820
- How come you missed it?
- I had a dreadful hangover yesterday.

492
00:44:19,990 --> 00:44:24,620
I went to a party on Monday night.
About four in the afternoon I went to bed.

493
00:44:24,790 --> 00:44:28,310
Took two sleeping pills.
I didn't know another thing.

494
00:44:28,470 --> 00:44:34,110
Till my father woke me this morning.
''I can't see,'' he said. ''I think I've gone blind.

495
00:44:34,270 --> 00:44:36,910
''Will you telephone for Dr Mayall?''

496
00:44:37,070 --> 00:44:42,390
The telephone wasn't working, and Anna
hadn't come down - she's the housekeeper.

497
00:44:42,550 --> 00:44:45,700
I discovered she'd gone blind too.

498
00:44:45,870 --> 00:44:48,910
(HAMMERING ON DOOR)

499
00:44:49,070 --> 00:44:52,350
It's all right. They can't get in.

500
00:44:52,510 --> 00:44:56,220
(MAN) Leave it! There's another pub near.

501
00:44:56,390 --> 00:44:59,030
I thought I was losing the panic.

502
00:45:00,270 --> 00:45:03,790
- It's been with me all morning.
- (MAN LAUGHING OUTSIDE)

503
00:45:03,950 --> 00:45:07,580
Half of me hasn't been able to take it all in,

504
00:45:07,750 --> 00:45:12,990
and the other half just doesn't know
how to begin to cope with it all.

505
00:45:13,150 --> 00:45:16,700
How many people do you think are left
who can see?

506
00:45:16,870 --> 00:45:20,550
I've met one...and a child. You haven't seen any?

507
00:45:20,710 --> 00:45:22,070
No.

508
00:45:22,230 --> 00:45:25,380
- I must get back to my father.
- Look, er...

509
00:45:25,550 --> 00:45:27,700
Do you mind if I come with you?

510
00:45:29,550 --> 00:45:32,150
I nearly asked you whether you would.

511
00:45:32,310 --> 00:45:36,190
But I thought there might be somebody
you wanted to get back to.

512
00:45:36,350 --> 00:45:41,300
No. My parents are dead
and I'm not married or anything.

513
00:45:42,550 --> 00:45:43,870
Here.

514
00:45:44,030 --> 00:45:46,950
It's not that I'm afraid of getting caught again.

515
00:45:47,110 --> 00:45:49,550
I'll watch out for that.

516
00:45:49,710 --> 00:45:53,020
It's just the dreadful sense of loneliness,

517
00:45:53,190 --> 00:45:56,310
being cut off from everybody else.

518
00:45:57,670 --> 00:45:59,660
Yeah, I know.

519
00:46:00,350 --> 00:46:02,950
Come on. Let's find a car with some petrol in.

520
00:46:13,350 --> 00:46:16,630
(RUSTLING)

521
00:46:16,790 --> 00:46:19,260
<i>(LOUD TAPPING)</i>

522
00:46:57,150 --> 00:46:59,790
- It's Anna.
- Triffid sting.

523
00:47:03,830 --> 00:47:06,550
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

524
00:47:19,270 --> 00:47:20,870
<i>(WHIPLASH SOUND )</i>

525
00:47:47,470 --> 00:47:50,670
The poison sacs are exhausted.

526
00:47:50,830 --> 00:47:54,430
It must have been doing a hell of a lot of stinging.

527
00:48:10,430 --> 00:48:13,110
- Is it your father?
- Yes.

528
00:48:13,750 --> 00:48:17,110
No! He's dead! There's nothing you can do.

529
00:48:17,270 --> 00:48:19,550
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

530
00:48:20,390 --> 00:48:21,990
Move!

531
00:48:22,150 --> 00:48:24,670
<i>(WHIPLASH SOUND )</i>

532
00:48:39,270 --> 00:48:41,950
(JO ) You think it was listening?

533
00:48:43,190 --> 00:48:45,790
They kill for food, don't they?

534
00:48:48,070 --> 00:48:50,990
<i>Go! Please, let's go!</i>

535
00:49:00,350 --> 00:49:02,910
It was listening.

536
00:49:30,310 --> 00:49:33,860
- They were driving her.
- Yes.

537
00:49:34,870 --> 00:49:39,740
I've a friend who used to say take away our sight
and our superiority's gone.

538
00:49:39,910 --> 00:49:44,350
You mean there's some connection between
the triffids and everyone going blind?

539
00:49:44,510 --> 00:49:46,660
No. I think it's a coincidence.

540
00:49:48,510 --> 00:49:53,670
(BILL) I know where we can get
some anti-triffid gear - guns, masks.

541
00:49:53,830 --> 00:49:56,950
I think we'd better go there now.

542
00:50:24,310 --> 00:50:28,230
- Is this it?
- Must be. He was driving.

543
00:50:28,390 --> 00:50:32,430
He can see. There's someone here who can see!

544
00:50:32,590 --> 00:50:35,190
- Get him out.
- Might be more than one.

545
00:50:35,350 --> 00:50:37,150
Where's the door?

546
00:50:37,310 --> 00:50:39,950
- Get him out!
- Get him out! Get him out!

547
00:50:40,110 --> 00:50:42,950
- We want him!
- Out, you bastard! Out!

548
00:50:43,110 --> 00:50:45,340
Out! Out! Out!

549
00:53:17,800 --> 00:53:20,910
- He's locked the door.
- You can see, can't you?

550
00:53:21,080 --> 00:53:24,150
- Find the back.
- Where is the back door?

551
00:53:25,600 --> 00:53:28,950
Get him out! Get him out! Get him out!

552
00:53:47,040 --> 00:53:49,950
Come out!

553
00:53:50,120 --> 00:53:53,270
- Come out!
- Let me get in there!

554
00:53:56,240 --> 00:54:00,350
You can see, you bastard!
You're staying with us!

555
00:54:24,720 --> 00:54:27,020
Wait! Here! This.

556
00:54:32,840 --> 00:54:35,550
(SHE SOBS)

557
00:54:37,960 --> 00:54:43,190
Hang on. We'll pick up those triffid guns
and find somewhere safe to stay, all right?

558
00:54:48,280 --> 00:54:51,980
<i>(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYS)</i>

559
00:55:02,160 --> 00:55:07,020
I've never seen a triffid climb
the side of a building, but just in case.

560
00:55:12,480 --> 00:55:15,790
- It's on the table if you want to eat.
- Right.

561
00:55:18,920 --> 00:55:20,910
Where the hell did you get that?

562
00:55:21,080 --> 00:55:24,270
Liberated it while your back was turned.

563
00:55:24,440 --> 00:55:28,430
It's just a gesture. Might be my last chance.

564
00:55:29,400 --> 00:55:31,430
It looks great.

565
00:55:31,600 --> 00:55:34,230
There's no cutlery, I'm afraid.

566
00:55:34,400 --> 00:55:37,990
That's a bit off!
I thought this was a show flat.

567
00:55:38,160 --> 00:55:41,470
Cutlery is kept in drawers.
It doesn't show.

568
00:55:41,640 --> 00:55:44,990
I got a couple of penknives on our shopping trip.

569
00:55:45,160 --> 00:55:47,750
They should do the job.

570
00:55:48,920 --> 00:55:53,550
Just think. All the labour
that went into building this place.

571
00:55:53,720 --> 00:55:56,150
We're probably the only people to use it.

572
00:55:56,320 --> 00:55:59,830
What will happen to this city if no one comes?

573
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:03,070
I suppose in time it'll just decay and collapse,

574
00:56:03,240 --> 00:56:07,470
like those places they keep finding
in the South American jungle.

575
00:56:08,320 --> 00:56:09,750
Oh!

576
00:56:09,920 --> 00:56:12,750
I didn't notice you liberate that!

577
00:56:12,920 --> 00:56:15,910
No point in leaving it to go bad.

578
00:56:16,080 --> 00:56:19,430
It's quite a good one, too,
judging from the price tag.

579
00:56:20,960 --> 00:56:25,270
Have a taste. I'm sure
your palate's better than mine.

580
00:56:25,440 --> 00:56:29,870
- What makes you say that?
- Nothing. I...I just...

581
00:56:30,040 --> 00:56:32,310
Assumed I was one of the filthy rich?

582
00:56:32,480 --> 00:56:36,070
No, I didn't mean that. I...

583
00:56:36,920 --> 00:56:39,590
Oh, look, taste it!

584
00:56:43,760 --> 00:56:45,950
Full-bodied.

585
00:56:49,440 --> 00:56:51,430
Mature.

586
00:56:51,600 --> 00:56:55,140
Just a touch pretentious, I'd have said!

587
00:56:55,320 --> 00:56:58,590
(GUNSHOTS AND SHOUTING OUTSIDE)

588
00:57:00,040 --> 00:57:02,670
Come on, let's eat.

589
00:57:02,840 --> 00:57:06,910
There's your penknife.
You can tell me your history.

590
00:57:07,080 --> 00:57:10,390
- Speak with your mouth full.
- Do you mind if I don't?

591
00:57:10,560 --> 00:57:13,550
- Not if it offends you.
- Go into history, I mean.

592
00:57:13,720 --> 00:57:16,790
- Rather not?
- There's nothing very exciting to hide.

593
00:57:16,960 --> 00:57:21,350
My mother died a year ago
and I went to live with my father.

594
00:57:21,520 --> 00:57:24,350
You're right. We were comfortably off.

595
00:57:24,520 --> 00:57:28,950
But all that, all the details of my life,
they were yesterday.

596
00:57:29,120 --> 00:57:31,110
It's the same with you.

597
00:57:31,280 --> 00:57:35,830
I think I'd like to know you from today,
and you know me from today.

598
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:40,860
You might not like what I was yesterday.
I might not like what you were.

599
00:57:41,040 --> 00:57:45,110
I don't want us to decide
that we don't like each other.

600
00:57:45,280 --> 00:57:47,630
I need your company.

601
00:57:48,600 --> 00:57:50,590
And I need yours.

602
00:57:50,760 --> 00:57:54,380
- So let's start from today, then.
- Fair enough.

603
00:57:57,720 --> 00:58:00,150
So what do we do?

604
00:58:00,320 --> 00:58:02,070
Well...

605
00:58:02,240 --> 00:58:06,830
The situation as I see it,
we've got to get out of London.

606
00:58:07,600 --> 00:58:10,910
There's still water in the tanks,
but soon there won't be.

607
00:58:11,080 --> 00:58:13,950
The city will begin to stink like a sewer.

608
00:58:14,120 --> 00:58:18,550
There are already corpses lying round.
Soon there'll be more.

609
00:58:18,720 --> 00:58:22,830
That may mean cholera, typhoid,
God knows what.

610
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:26,390
It's important to get out
before that kind of thing starts.

611
00:58:27,600 --> 00:58:29,310
So...

612
00:58:29,480 --> 00:58:32,470
Where do we go? Any ideas?

613
00:58:32,640 --> 00:58:37,870
Somewhere out of the way...
with its own water supply. A well, perhaps.

614
00:58:38,040 --> 00:58:42,150
And as high up as possible for a good, clean wind.

615
00:58:42,320 --> 00:58:45,750
Lake District, Cornwall, Exmoor, Wales...

616
00:58:46,600 --> 00:58:50,190
We'll have to get to towns for supplies
once it's safe again.

617
00:58:50,360 --> 00:58:52,630
- How long will that be?
- I don't know.

618
00:58:52,800 --> 00:58:56,910
How about Sussex?
The South Downs. I know a place there.

619
00:58:57,080 --> 00:59:00,430
<i>It's a beautiful old farmhouse
overlooking Pulborough.</i>

620
00:59:00,600 --> 00:59:04,950
It's not very high up.
But Dennis and Mary, they're great.

621
00:59:05,120 --> 00:59:08,660
They're real do-it-yourself environment freaks.

622
00:59:08,840 --> 00:59:15,390
A wind pump for water...
Make their own electricity. All that sort of thing.

623
00:59:15,560 --> 00:59:19,670
Sounds ideal. A bit heavily populated
round there, but...

624
00:59:20,440 --> 00:59:23,510
Look, let's leave the choice
of the place for a moment

625
00:59:23,680 --> 00:59:26,110
and get down to what we need to do first.

626
00:59:26,280 --> 00:59:29,150
Let's make a list. I like lists!

627
00:59:29,800 --> 00:59:31,790
Now, then...

628
00:59:35,920 --> 00:59:37,790
Oh, ta.

629
00:59:49,760 --> 00:59:51,870
- Bill...
- Hmm?

630
01:00:02,520 --> 01:00:05,790
- A signal.
- It means there's someone else who can see.

631
01:00:10,280 --> 01:00:13,030
What are you doing?

632
01:00:13,200 --> 01:00:16,350
Marking the position so we can find it tomorrow.

633
01:00:16,520 --> 01:00:19,150
Too dangerous to go out tonight.

634
01:00:19,320 --> 01:00:24,670
It's the university tower, I think, but I'm not sure.
Anyway, better going in daylight.

635
01:00:26,400 --> 01:00:29,790
For all we know, it could be a trap.

636
01:00:52,600 --> 01:00:54,470
Got them!

637
01:01:14,760 --> 01:01:17,110
Coming back, dear.

638
01:01:17,280 --> 01:01:18,990
<i>(WHIPLASH SOUND )</i>

639
01:01:19,160 --> 01:01:21,950
(BREAKING GLASS)

640
01:01:22,120 --> 01:01:23,590
Tom?

641
01:01:24,320 --> 01:01:26,470
Tom? Tom, what is it?

642
01:01:29,880 --> 01:01:31,190
Tom?

643
01:01:35,240 --> 01:01:37,110
Tom?

644
01:01:42,760 --> 01:01:46,110
(BREAKING GLASS IN DISTANCE)

645
01:01:57,920 --> 01:02:01,310
(MAN IN DISTANCE)
For God's sake, help us!

646
01:02:12,760 --> 01:02:16,870
(WOMAN SOBS IN DISTANCE)

647
01:02:20,480 --> 01:02:22,910
Do you hear those poor people?

648
01:02:23,080 --> 01:02:26,310
(SOBBING CONTINUES)

649
01:02:37,400 --> 01:02:40,270
(CRASHING AND BANGING)

650
01:02:56,360 --> 01:02:58,390
(MAN) You listen to me.

651
01:02:58,560 --> 01:03:03,630
These people have got just as much
bloody right to live as you have.

652
01:03:03,800 --> 01:03:09,830
It's not their fault they're blind, but it is
gonna be your bloody fault if they starve!

653
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:12,870
- There's nothing we can do.
- Of course there is.

654
01:03:13,040 --> 01:03:18,310
What do you think I've been doing?
I've been showing them where to find food.

655
01:03:18,480 --> 01:03:20,910
That's what they need - food!

656
01:03:21,080 --> 01:03:25,070
There's thousands of them out there.
There's tons of food.

657
01:03:28,360 --> 01:03:33,630
You could be showing them where it is.
But what are you doing? I'll tell you.

658
01:03:33,800 --> 01:03:38,270
You're bloody well looking after your own skins.
Damn you, Jack, I'm all right!

659
01:03:38,440 --> 01:03:42,350
- Let's try round the back.
- (MAN) Of course you could.

660
01:03:42,520 --> 01:03:45,870
All you've got to do is to help me to show them.

661
01:03:46,040 --> 01:03:49,070
God almighty, aren't you bloody well human?!

662
01:03:51,480 --> 01:03:55,550
(ARMY MAN) Use your head.
How long do you think that food will last?

663
01:03:55,720 --> 01:03:58,350
How the hell do I know?

664
01:03:58,520 --> 01:04:01,310
But if bastards like you don't come and help,

665
01:04:01,480 --> 01:04:06,150
there aren't gonna be many left alive
by the time they clear this mess up.

666
01:04:06,320 --> 01:04:09,070
I know why you won't come and help.

667
01:04:09,240 --> 01:04:14,310
You're scared bloody stiff if they get it,
there'll be less left for you!

668
01:04:22,360 --> 01:04:27,670
Look, you can come in by yourself
or you can clear off.

669
01:04:30,480 --> 01:04:32,710
Hold on to that, brother.

670
01:04:32,880 --> 01:04:35,340
I'll sort you bloody lot out.

671
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:39,390
(GUNSHOTS AND SCREAMING)

672
01:04:44,640 --> 01:04:47,510
Tom! George!

673
01:04:48,920 --> 01:04:51,830
Stay your ground!

674
01:05:09,920 --> 01:05:14,830
They've all gone. No one was hurt.
They fired over their heads.

675
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:17,300
<i>Poor devils couldn't see to know that.</i>

676
01:05:18,320 --> 01:05:21,150
God, they must have been terrified.

677
01:05:21,320 --> 01:05:23,190
Yeah.

678
01:05:24,800 --> 01:05:27,510
- Can I have a cigarette?
- Yeah.

679
01:05:27,680 --> 01:05:29,030
Ta.

680
01:05:30,200 --> 01:05:33,190
He's right, isn't he, that man?

681
01:05:33,360 --> 01:05:35,950
We've got to help them.

682
01:05:36,680 --> 01:05:39,550
He's right. And he's wrong.

683
01:05:40,960 --> 01:05:45,310
I don't think there is anyone over the horizon
who'll clear this mess up.

684
01:05:45,480 --> 01:05:47,710
It won't be cleared up.

685
01:05:47,880 --> 01:05:52,950
We could show some of them
where to find food for a few days or weeks.

686
01:05:53,120 --> 01:05:57,110
- But what happens afterwards?
- So we should leave them to rot?

687
01:05:57,280 --> 01:06:01,230
I think it comes to a very simple choice.

688
01:06:01,400 --> 01:06:04,910
Either we say, ''There's been a catastrophe.

689
01:06:05,080 --> 01:06:09,470
''Let's start again.
Let's save what can be saved...''

690
01:06:10,600 --> 01:06:14,030
Or we say, ''No, those people will die.

691
01:06:14,200 --> 01:06:17,390
''We must keep them alive as long as possible.''

692
01:06:17,560 --> 01:06:21,340
On the face of it, that's the most humane choice.

693
01:06:21,520 --> 01:06:24,150
For us, it's probably suicide.

694
01:06:25,160 --> 01:06:28,430
We'd die. They'd die. We'd all die.

695
01:06:31,960 --> 01:06:35,710
Would that be making the best use of ourselves?

696
01:06:35,880 --> 01:06:38,710
- You've made up your mind.
- Look...

697
01:06:38,880 --> 01:06:41,440
I don't like it any more than you do.

698
01:06:41,600 --> 01:06:46,310
But in the end do we make a moral gesture?
That's all it can be, a gesture!

699
01:06:46,480 --> 01:06:51,600
Or do we join those people in there?
Start to rebuild some kind of life for ourselves?

700
01:06:53,880 --> 01:06:56,230
They intend to survive.

701
01:06:59,040 --> 01:07:04,310
It's going to be a pretty strange
sort of world that's left to survive in.

702
01:07:05,960 --> 01:07:08,470
I don't think we're going to like it a lot.

703
01:07:16,400 --> 01:07:19,030
(HORN TOOTS)

704
01:07:27,800 --> 01:07:29,190
Morning.

705
01:07:34,600 --> 01:07:38,710
I'll give you a rough idea of how things stand.
There's about 35 of us.

706
01:07:38,880 --> 01:07:41,260
All sorts of people.

707
01:07:41,440 --> 01:07:44,670
We hope that more will come in. Coffee?

708
01:07:44,840 --> 01:07:47,550
Out of those here now, most of them can see.

709
01:07:47,720 --> 01:07:52,870
The rest are wives and husbands.
And there are two or three blind children.

710
01:07:53,040 --> 01:07:59,030
Sit down. The general idea is that we move out
of here tomorrow, if you can be ready,

711
01:07:59,200 --> 01:08:02,350
to be on the safe side, you understand.

712
01:08:02,520 --> 01:08:05,910
We decided to go this evening
for the same reason.

713
01:08:06,080 --> 01:08:10,190
- Have you got any supplies?
- Not yet. We've gotta do that today.

714
01:08:10,360 --> 01:08:13,030
- We do have anti-triffid gear.
- Oh?

715
01:08:13,200 --> 01:08:16,900
Why do you give that such priority? Do sit down.

716
01:08:17,080 --> 01:08:22,470
We know that a certain number have escaped,
probably from the zoo.

717
01:08:22,640 --> 01:08:24,670
<i>We've seen them near Regent's Park.</i>

718
01:08:24,840 --> 01:08:27,910
They killed my father
and the woman who worked for him.

719
01:08:28,080 --> 01:08:32,870
I'm sorry to hear that.
I know that triffids can be very nasty

720
01:08:33,040 --> 01:08:39,470
in parts of the world where they're not controlled,
but I think here they're a limited problem.

721
01:08:39,640 --> 01:08:42,870
Go ahead.
Most of them are well fenced-in.

722
01:08:43,040 --> 01:08:46,630
They break down fences
if they're not properly watched.

723
01:08:46,800 --> 01:08:50,670
- I used to work on a triffid farm.
- Then I bow to your experience.

724
01:08:50,840 --> 01:08:54,950
Anyway, today we must get everything
together which we need to take.

725
01:08:55,120 --> 01:08:59,070
Here's a list. Find a lorry,
or two if you can both drive one.

726
01:08:59,240 --> 01:09:01,510
- I think I can.
- Good.

727
01:09:01,680 --> 01:09:04,390
Here's the addresses of some warehouses.

728
01:09:04,560 --> 01:09:08,340
Stick to the list - cans and packets of food.

729
01:09:08,520 --> 01:09:11,590
We don't want a duplication of goods.

730
01:09:11,760 --> 01:09:15,510
There's a meeting this evening
to discuss everything. Got a pistol?

731
01:09:15,680 --> 01:09:17,030
No.

732
01:09:23,400 --> 01:09:25,390
- No.
- Better, just in case.

733
01:09:26,280 --> 01:09:30,430
- No, I don't think so, thank you.
- Fire into the air. It's effective.

734
01:09:30,600 --> 01:09:32,790
We've got to survive.

735
01:09:54,240 --> 01:09:55,550
Thank you.

736
01:09:55,720 --> 01:09:59,310
Two days ago, we'd have been arrested for this.

737
01:10:20,440 --> 01:10:24,950
Hey, don't think about it. Let's just keep working.

738
01:10:41,920 --> 01:10:44,790
Very good. Excellent!

739
01:10:48,480 --> 01:10:53,230
- What are these?
- That's the anti-triffid gear.

740
01:10:53,400 --> 01:10:55,780
Guns, masks, suits, that sort of thing.

741
01:10:55,960 --> 01:10:59,310
Did you see any triffids while you were out?

742
01:10:59,480 --> 01:11:01,860
Not this time, no.

743
01:11:03,040 --> 01:11:07,750
There have been no reports
of sightings by anyone else.

744
01:11:07,920 --> 01:11:12,110
There won't be many in the centre of London.
It's like a desert to them.

745
01:11:12,280 --> 01:11:17,550
They need soil for their roots, so they'll move
to the country, which is where we're going!

746
01:11:17,720 --> 01:11:22,550
Look, we've done our bit -
got two loads of food. We're taking that gear!

747
01:11:25,360 --> 01:11:28,670
All right. If it doesn't take up very much room.

748
01:11:31,160 --> 01:11:34,550
Don't forget the meeting at half past nine.

749
01:11:38,120 --> 01:11:41,900
He thinks I'm bananas.
Well, he's got a shock coming.

750
01:11:43,720 --> 01:11:46,630
Good evening, ladies and gentlemen.

751
01:11:48,520 --> 01:11:51,550
As you possibly know,
my name is Michael Beadley.

752
01:11:51,720 --> 01:11:55,590
This is Elspeth Carey, Dr Vorless,
our medical officer Miss Burgh,

753
01:11:55,760 --> 01:11:57,910
and Major Anderson.

754
01:11:58,080 --> 01:12:02,190
We are a self-elected committee.
Since speed and organisation are essential,

755
01:12:02,360 --> 01:12:06,350
there's been no time for democratic formalities.

756
01:12:06,520 --> 01:12:12,510
We intend to establish a community
of those who've survived the catastrophe,

757
01:12:12,680 --> 01:12:17,800
and we wish to set before you the facts
as we see them and the future as we see it.

758
01:12:19,120 --> 01:12:21,870
Tomorrow, we leave London.

759
01:12:22,040 --> 01:12:26,750
Tonight, therefore, you must decide
whether you wish to join with us,

760
01:12:26,920 --> 01:12:29,670
or whether your views are so different from ours

761
01:12:29,840 --> 01:12:33,310
that you would prefer
to set up a group of your own.

762
01:12:33,480 --> 01:12:36,040
The choice is yours.

763
01:12:38,480 --> 01:12:41,110
The world as we knew it has ended.

764
01:12:41,280 --> 01:12:46,300
Some of us may be feeling
it is the end of everything. But it isn't.

765
01:12:46,480 --> 01:12:50,180
It can be, if we allow it.

766
01:12:51,760 --> 01:12:57,150
During the last 35 years, the earth could
have been destroyed by a nuclear holocaust.

767
01:12:57,320 --> 01:13:00,710
The earth has not been destroyed.

768
01:13:00,880 --> 01:13:04,190
It can still provide us with food and raw materials.

769
01:13:04,360 --> 01:13:09,270
We have repositories of knowledge that can
teach us to do anything we have done before.

770
01:13:09,440 --> 01:13:11,510
We have the means.

771
01:13:11,680 --> 01:13:16,750
And we have the health and the strength
to begin to build again.

772
01:13:18,080 --> 01:13:20,670
Major Anderson will say a few words.

773
01:13:20,840 --> 01:13:22,630
Thank you.

774
01:13:22,800 --> 01:13:25,070
Good evening.

775
01:13:25,240 --> 01:13:27,800
The convoy will depart at 1200 hours.

776
01:13:27,960 --> 01:13:31,470
We cannot risk infection
by stopping longer than this.

777
01:13:31,640 --> 01:13:36,870
We have obtained certain vaccines
with which our medical officer will inoculate us.

778
01:13:37,040 --> 01:13:41,150
But we cannot protect ourselves
against all disease.

779
01:13:41,320 --> 01:13:48,030
Any epidemic amongst us will wipe us out
or, at best, seriously reduce our number.

780
01:13:48,200 --> 01:13:54,460
For this reason, we have been gathering
so many of the basic necessities of life.

781
01:13:56,040 --> 01:13:58,230
For a minimum of one year,

782
01:13:58,400 --> 01:14:03,420
we shall have to exist in what will be
virtually a state of siege.

783
01:14:03,600 --> 01:14:06,470
(WOMAN) It is the future which is important.

784
01:14:06,640 --> 01:14:11,070
All of us will have our parts to play
in creating that future.

785
01:14:11,240 --> 01:14:13,830
The men must work.

786
01:14:14,000 --> 01:14:16,430
The women must have babies.

787
01:14:16,600 --> 01:14:20,220
We can support a limited number
of women who cannot see,

788
01:14:20,400 --> 01:14:24,070
because they will have babies who can see.

789
01:14:24,240 --> 01:14:27,470
We cannot support men who cannot see.

790
01:14:27,640 --> 01:14:32,910
In our community, babies will be
more important than husbands.

791
01:14:33,080 --> 01:14:38,830
It follows from this that the one man/
one woman relationship as we understand it

792
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:42,950
will probably become an illogical luxury.

793
01:14:43,120 --> 01:14:46,470
We shall find that in many aspects of our lives,

794
01:14:46,640 --> 01:14:50,230
the laws as we knew them
have been abolished by circumstances,

795
01:14:50,400 --> 01:14:56,390
and it will fall to us to make new laws suitable
for the conditions in which we find ourselves.

796
01:14:58,040 --> 01:15:01,630
Unless you find all this totally acceptable,

797
01:15:01,800 --> 01:15:05,830
there is absolutely no point
in even thinking of joining us.

798
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:10,110
(QUIET DISCUSSION)

799
01:15:15,600 --> 01:15:20,070
- How many do you think will join?
- Nearly all of them.

800
01:15:21,800 --> 01:15:25,790
- Some women didn't like the sex angle.
- They'll come round to it.

801
01:15:25,960 --> 01:15:29,950
What's the choice? To have babies
and a community to look after you,

802
01:15:30,120 --> 01:15:32,580
or no babies and no one to look after you.

803
01:15:32,760 --> 01:15:37,910
Most women want babies.
A husband is just a logical means to an end!

804
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:44,430
What do you think the arrangements will be?

805
01:15:44,600 --> 01:15:47,790
They're taking some women who can't see.

806
01:15:49,000 --> 01:15:53,430
So I think it'll be every man
who marries a girl who can see

807
01:15:53,600 --> 01:15:56,510
must also take on one or two blind girls.

808
01:15:56,680 --> 01:15:59,060
- Makes sense.
- Yeah.

809
01:15:59,240 --> 01:16:02,510
If I've got to have three wives...

810
01:16:04,840 --> 01:16:07,470
..will you be one?

811
01:16:07,640 --> 01:16:10,990
- On one condition.
- What?

812
01:16:11,160 --> 01:16:14,190
I pick the other two.

813
01:16:26,880 --> 01:16:30,990
So, what's the arrangements for tonight, then?

814
01:16:31,160 --> 01:16:36,510
Strict segregation into dormitories.
There's no promiscuity till they say so.

815
01:16:43,400 --> 01:16:47,590
(BELL RINGS)
(MAN) Fire! Fire!

816
01:16:47,760 --> 01:16:50,630
Fire! Fire!

817
01:16:50,800 --> 01:16:55,270
The women are all right. They've got
a separate way out. Get down the stairs.

818
01:18:49,080 --> 01:18:54,100
The women are all right. They've got
a separate way out. Get down the stairs.

819
01:19:55,000 --> 01:19:57,990
(KEY TURNS IN LOCK)

820
01:20:00,280 --> 01:20:04,350
- (MAN) You come to?
- What the hell's going on?

821
01:20:04,520 --> 01:20:07,150
- Want a cup of tea?
- Why am I tied up?

822
01:20:07,320 --> 01:20:12,110
Tell me where you are, I'll bring you the tea.

823
01:20:14,480 --> 01:20:17,230
I'll go to the bed. Hang on.

824
01:20:21,240 --> 01:20:23,540
Lock up, Ted.

825
01:20:28,600 --> 01:20:31,550
- Ta.
- There's a drop of rum in it.

826
01:20:34,280 --> 01:20:37,190
- What's your name?
- Bill.

827
01:20:37,360 --> 01:20:40,150
Oh. I'm Alf.

828
01:20:41,520 --> 01:20:44,830
- Want a fag?
- Yeah. Ta.

829
01:20:45,000 --> 01:20:48,390
Don't thank me. Everything's free nowadays.

830
01:20:48,560 --> 01:20:50,110
(CHUCKLES)

831
01:20:50,280 --> 01:20:52,660
You have to look on the bright side.

832
01:20:55,240 --> 01:20:59,430
- My hands seem to be tied.
- Ah. Coker's orders.

833
01:20:59,600 --> 01:21:04,110
- Who's Coker?
- Didn't you hear him yesterday at the university?

834
01:21:04,280 --> 01:21:07,900
He was trying to get those bastards to help us.

835
01:21:08,080 --> 01:21:10,830
All they did was shoot at us.

836
01:21:13,400 --> 01:21:16,150
So Coker said they'd get what was coming to 'em.

837
01:21:16,320 --> 01:21:20,910
He met up with a couple of others
who could see and they fixed it.

838
01:21:21,080 --> 01:21:24,950
- You mean there wasn't a fire?
- Course there was a fire!

839
01:21:25,120 --> 01:21:29,190
A sort of fire. They lit some paper,
rang a bell and shouted ''Fire!''

840
01:21:29,360 --> 01:21:32,430
They fixed up some trip-wires on the stairs.

841
01:21:32,600 --> 01:21:37,070
We knobbled as many of you as we could.
Coker's making us into parties.

842
01:21:37,240 --> 01:21:41,510
We'll put one of you into each party.
You're the eyes for the rest.

843
01:21:41,680 --> 01:21:45,990
You keep us going
till someone comes along to rescue all of us.

844
01:21:47,600 --> 01:21:49,310
I see.

845
01:21:50,920 --> 01:21:54,350
You reckon that's gonna be a long time?

846
01:21:54,520 --> 01:21:56,630
(KEY TURNS IN LOCK)

847
01:21:59,440 --> 01:22:01,790
My name's Jack Coker.

848
01:22:01,960 --> 01:22:07,470
That's your area. Your party works only that area.

849
01:22:07,640 --> 01:22:12,660
Your job is to find any food that's going,
see that your party gets it

850
01:22:12,840 --> 01:22:14,910
and anything else they may need.

851
01:22:15,080 --> 01:22:17,430
Understand?

852
01:22:17,600 --> 01:22:19,190
Or what?

853
01:22:19,360 --> 01:22:23,510
Or they'll get hungry, and some of them
are tough. We're not doing it for fun.

854
01:22:23,680 --> 01:22:26,390
Anyway, you'll be handcuffed to Ted and Alf.

855
01:22:26,560 --> 01:22:29,630
- How will I be able to do the work?
- You won't.

856
01:22:29,800 --> 01:22:35,310
You tell them what to do. When you're released,
as sometimes you'll have to be,

857
01:22:35,480 --> 01:22:39,950
they've got a chain and cuffs
so that one leg and one arm can be locked

858
01:22:40,120 --> 01:22:44,110
to a bedstead or pipe
before your handcuffs are undone.

859
01:22:44,280 --> 01:22:48,190
- You've got it all worked out!
- Tomorrow we'll run you up there.

860
01:22:48,360 --> 01:22:53,220
You have to look for somewhere to live.
A hotel or boarding house.

861
01:22:53,400 --> 01:22:56,630
The beds would be there. That's up to you.

862
01:22:56,800 --> 01:23:02,630
Once we dump you, you're on your own.
Until somebody comes to tidy things up.

863
01:23:02,800 --> 01:23:05,750
- What if nobody comes?
- They've got to come.

864
01:23:05,920 --> 01:23:10,430
You concentrate on doing your job.
Stick to your area.

865
01:23:11,840 --> 01:23:15,950
<i>Can I ask you something?
Have you got a Miss Payton staying here?</i>

866
01:23:16,120 --> 01:23:18,270
- Josella.
- I don't know their names.

867
01:23:18,440 --> 01:23:20,950
- Tall, blonde, about 23?
- I think so.

868
01:23:21,120 --> 01:23:25,150
- Tell her...
- I've got more important things to do.

869
01:23:26,520 --> 01:23:30,350
Those people are totally dependent on you.

870
01:23:30,520 --> 01:23:34,910
You may try and run out on them -
you may even find it's possible.

871
01:23:36,120 --> 01:23:41,390
But I don't think you'll do it.
You'd be condemning them to die.

872
01:23:48,560 --> 01:23:54,110
What do you make of Jack Coker?
Is he round the twist to stick with us?

873
01:23:54,280 --> 01:23:55,870
No.

874
01:23:57,320 --> 01:24:02,510
That girl, she's with the group
what's going to Victoria and Westminster.

875
01:24:02,680 --> 01:24:06,430
- I told her you was OK.
- Thanks.

876
01:24:12,680 --> 01:24:16,150
<i>Put your head down. OK, you're all right.</i>

877
01:24:32,040 --> 01:24:34,470
Right. Off you go.

878
01:24:47,840 --> 01:24:51,150
- Is that the man who can see?
- Yeah.

879
01:24:54,640 --> 01:24:59,710
- It's very kind of you to come with us.
- He's got no bloody choice, girl!

880
01:24:59,880 --> 01:25:01,950
Believe you me!

881
01:25:17,720 --> 01:25:22,190
You can't come here. Tell him they can't come!

882
01:25:26,280 --> 01:25:29,270
Have you got anybody
staying here at the moment?

883
01:25:29,440 --> 01:25:33,430
There's some people left -
three or four. None of us can see.

884
01:25:33,600 --> 01:25:37,300
Look, if they've got rooms, we're having 'em.

885
01:25:37,480 --> 01:25:42,110
- There's not enough food left for us!
- If we want it, we'll take your food.

886
01:25:42,280 --> 01:25:44,950
- Shut up, will you?
- Watch your lip, mate!

887
01:25:45,120 --> 01:25:48,630
- I'll smash your face in!
- Oh, very clever! Then what?

888
01:25:48,800 --> 01:25:51,390
He's right. Just shut it, Ted.

889
01:25:52,640 --> 01:25:56,950
Look, madam,
I don't think you quite understand.

890
01:25:57,120 --> 01:26:00,190
We're here to get food. I can see.

891
01:26:00,360 --> 01:26:03,830
My job is to find food and bring it back here.

892
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:07,470
You and your husband can have a share of it.

893
01:26:07,640 --> 01:26:10,870
It's a very fair offer. I hope you'll agree.

894
01:26:11,040 --> 01:26:15,790
If not, then I'm afraid you're gonna
have to find somewhere else to stay.

895
01:26:19,840 --> 01:26:21,790
I'm sorry.

896
01:26:21,960 --> 01:26:24,340
But it's the only way.

897
01:26:30,160 --> 01:26:32,910
(DISTANT SINGING)

898
01:26:33,080 --> 01:26:36,510
# I'm tired and I wanna go to bed

899
01:26:38,360 --> 01:26:41,350
# I had a little drink about an hour ago

900
01:26:41,520 --> 01:26:44,910
# And it's gone right to my head #

901
01:26:45,480 --> 01:26:47,110
(BILL) Stop!

902
01:26:50,880 --> 01:26:53,470
- Are you all right, Frank?
- I think so.

903
01:26:53,640 --> 01:26:57,750
You've cut your mouth, that's all.
You wanna watch what you're doing.

904
01:26:57,920 --> 01:27:00,870
- Very funny (!)
- Got to stay sane, pal.

905
01:27:01,040 --> 01:27:03,470
Come on. On your feet.

906
01:27:03,640 --> 01:27:05,870
That's it.

907
01:27:06,040 --> 01:27:09,740
Here's your box. Feel it?

908
01:27:09,920 --> 01:27:13,430
<i>Pick it up. That's it.</i>

909
01:27:13,600 --> 01:27:17,630
Back in the line. That's it.
Come on. Back up there.

910
01:27:18,720 --> 01:27:20,550
That's it.

911
01:27:20,720 --> 01:27:23,630
Right. We'll move forward to the cart.

912
01:27:23,800 --> 01:27:27,830
When I say stop, we'll unload one box at a time.

913
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:33,150
Go to the front of the cart when
what you're carrying has been taken. All right?

914
01:27:34,640 --> 01:27:36,470
Right.

915
01:27:39,200 --> 01:27:44,870
<i>(BILL) My dear Jo, it's a bit stupid,
writing a letter that can never be posted</i>

916
01:27:45,040 --> 01:27:47,790
<i>to someone whose address is unknown.</i>

917
01:27:47,960 --> 01:27:53,710
<i>But if I can't see you
or hold you or make love to you,</i>

918
01:27:53,880 --> 01:27:56,750
<i>I can at least pretend I'm talking to you.</i>

919
01:27:56,920 --> 01:28:00,430
<i>And one day I promise
I shall deliver this by hand.</i>

920
01:28:01,880 --> 01:28:04,340
<i>One day.</i>

921
01:28:04,520 --> 01:28:08,830
<i>I've been here for four days, and each day
it seems more difficult to leave.</i>

922
01:28:10,800 --> 01:28:12,870
Next man forward!

923
01:28:13,040 --> 01:28:17,950
<i>At the moment there's little they can do
unless I'm there to supervise.</i>

924
01:28:18,120 --> 01:28:20,830
<i>They try. Oh, yes.</i>

925
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:24,310
<i>Most of them try so desperately hard...</i>

926
01:28:26,840 --> 01:28:29,590
<i>..to watch them...</i>

927
01:28:31,160 --> 01:28:35,190
<i>..is almost heartbreaking.</i>

928
01:28:37,560 --> 01:28:40,020
<i>But will it take...</i>

929
01:28:40,880 --> 01:28:44,710
<i>..days or weeks or...</i>

930
01:28:48,120 --> 01:28:50,190
<i>Dearest Jo,</i>

931
01:28:50,360 --> 01:28:52,820
<i>I so wish...</i>

932
01:29:06,360 --> 01:29:10,910
They've got to be taken out of here
or whatever they've got will spread.

933
01:29:11,080 --> 01:29:14,470
There's an empty house next door.
We'll take them there.

934
01:29:14,640 --> 01:29:17,470
One of the women can look after them.

935
01:29:17,640 --> 01:29:21,630
I'll go to a chemist and get something
to make sure they're not in pain.

936
01:29:21,800 --> 01:29:27,070
That's all we can do for them.
It's the rest of you we've got to think about.

937
01:29:38,000 --> 01:29:39,350
Stop!

938
01:29:47,960 --> 01:29:49,630
Forwards.

939
01:30:20,600 --> 01:30:22,270
Come on!

940
01:30:22,440 --> 01:30:24,630
(BILL) Move!

941
01:30:26,600 --> 01:30:28,900
Stay here. Shan't be long.

942
01:30:29,080 --> 01:30:30,910
<i>Put him down.</i>

943
01:30:35,120 --> 01:30:37,750
He's dead. Get these cuffs off.

944
01:30:39,280 --> 01:30:43,470
You lot! Move forward till you hit the fence,
then follow it around.

945
01:30:43,640 --> 01:30:45,070
Move!

946
01:30:45,600 --> 01:30:47,350
Come on!

947
01:30:51,720 --> 01:30:54,150
- Give me the keys.
- Get stuffed!

948
01:30:54,320 --> 01:30:57,750
- I'm useless like this!
- You're staying with me!

949
01:31:28,680 --> 01:31:31,270
(GUNSHOT)

950
01:31:39,680 --> 01:31:44,230
There's two more been taken ill in the same way.
A man and a woman.

951
01:31:44,400 --> 01:31:47,670
- We took them through to the empty house.
- Good.

952
01:31:48,440 --> 01:31:50,070
Here.

953
01:31:50,240 --> 01:31:54,230
Look, I'm gonna take another party out
in the morning.

954
01:31:54,400 --> 01:31:58,950
There's some good shops in Hampstead,
and I can drive now my hands are free.

955
01:31:59,120 --> 01:32:02,230
While I'm out, keep the door locked and bolted

956
01:32:02,400 --> 01:32:04,960
in case that mob find out where we are.

957
01:32:21,560 --> 01:32:25,510
This way. Come on. That's it. Mind the step.

958
01:32:26,760 --> 01:32:30,990
There's glass in the door.
Mind the glass. That way.

959
01:32:31,160 --> 01:32:34,670
Feel for the shelves. Follow them round.

960
01:32:34,840 --> 01:32:36,990
Mind the glass.

961
01:32:53,200 --> 01:32:55,660
- Chain gang, Bob.
- Yeah.

962
01:32:55,840 --> 01:33:00,310
Everything from these shelves.
Fill the baskets, pass them along.

963
01:33:00,480 --> 01:33:03,910
There's a cellar. I'm going to investigate.

964
01:33:09,640 --> 01:33:11,470
(MAN) Agh! Agh!

965
01:33:11,640 --> 01:33:13,790
(COMMOTION)

966
01:33:13,960 --> 01:33:15,670
(MAN) Agh!

967
01:33:19,080 --> 01:33:21,430
- Bill, where are you?
- Where is he?

968
01:33:21,600 --> 01:33:24,710
(COMMOTION CONTINUES)

969
01:33:31,280 --> 01:33:33,270
- Bill!
- Bill!

970
01:33:33,440 --> 01:33:35,740
(MAN SCREAMS)

971
01:33:48,560 --> 01:33:51,630
It's all right. There's another way out.

972
01:33:51,800 --> 01:33:54,790
Come towards me. This way. Mind your feet.

973
01:33:54,960 --> 01:33:56,990
<i>Lift your feet. Put the basket down.</i>

974
01:33:57,160 --> 01:34:00,430
- This way. Towards me.
- Where are we going?

975
01:34:00,600 --> 01:34:02,790
Two steps. Two steps.

976
01:34:02,960 --> 01:34:06,500
- That's it.
- Take it easy!

977
01:34:06,680 --> 01:34:08,870
For God's sake, go easy!

978
01:34:10,240 --> 01:34:14,230
That's it. Now just hold it there. Hold it there.

979
01:34:22,840 --> 01:34:28,230
We're gonna have to try this way.
It's the triffids, so no noise at all.

980
01:34:28,400 --> 01:34:32,230
Those damn things react to anything.
There's a table.

981
01:34:32,400 --> 01:34:35,630
Slide along the table until you hit the window sill.

982
01:34:40,560 --> 01:34:42,550
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

983
01:34:58,200 --> 01:35:00,190
(GLASS SMASHES)

984
01:35:38,280 --> 01:35:41,510
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

985
01:36:02,880 --> 01:36:05,870
(ENGINE STARTS)

986
01:36:30,960 --> 01:36:33,420
(ENGINE REVS)

987
01:36:44,960 --> 01:36:47,190
- Bill?
- Yeah.

988
01:36:50,840 --> 01:36:53,710
Two more have died.
Two of those we took next door.

989
01:36:53,880 --> 01:36:58,310
Another one will die tonight.
Three more upstairs are very ill.

990
01:37:11,480 --> 01:37:13,710
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

991
01:37:13,880 --> 01:37:15,870
Who's that?

992
01:37:16,040 --> 01:37:18,230
Oh. It is you.

993
01:37:21,160 --> 01:37:23,190
Are you alone?

994
01:37:23,360 --> 01:37:25,790
Yeah. What do you want?

995
01:37:35,760 --> 01:37:38,710
You're going away, aren't you?

996
01:37:38,880 --> 01:37:40,870
I've never said that.

997
01:37:41,040 --> 01:37:44,740
They're all saying it.
And they're right, aren't they?

998
01:37:48,240 --> 01:37:53,150
You can't. You can't leave them like this.
They need you.

999
01:37:55,600 --> 01:37:58,190
I'm not doing any good.

1000
01:37:59,480 --> 01:38:02,390
I'm afraid all those hopes were false.

1001
01:38:02,560 --> 01:38:08,070
- But what if they weren't?
- We'd have heard something by now.

1002
01:38:08,240 --> 01:38:10,990
But if they come and you've just walked out...

1003
01:38:11,160 --> 01:38:14,630
Do you think I haven't thought of that?!

1004
01:38:14,800 --> 01:38:17,070
I'm doing no good.

1005
01:38:17,240 --> 01:38:21,310
I'm like a drug they give to patients
to keep them going a bit longer.

1006
01:38:21,480 --> 01:38:24,040
I can't save anybody.

1007
01:38:27,960 --> 01:38:30,110
It's still better to be alive.

1008
01:38:30,280 --> 01:38:32,550
Even like this.

1009
01:38:33,160 --> 01:38:35,790
You can keep us going.

1010
01:38:37,880 --> 01:38:40,710
There's always a chance.

1011
01:38:44,520 --> 01:38:45,950
They...

1012
01:38:48,080 --> 01:38:51,070
They said you might be lonely.

1013
01:38:52,160 --> 01:38:54,150
They said...

1014
01:38:54,320 --> 01:38:57,470
perhaps if you had somebody with you...

1015
01:38:58,680 --> 01:39:01,110
somebody here...

1016
01:39:02,240 --> 01:39:04,950
..you might not want to leave us.

1017
01:39:06,600 --> 01:39:10,470
<i>- Perhaps you'd stay with us.
- Oh, God...</i>

1018
01:39:13,240 --> 01:39:16,510
You'd be kind to me, wouldn't you? I haven't...

1019
01:39:16,680 --> 01:39:18,150
Stop it!

1020
01:39:18,320 --> 01:39:21,270
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

1021
01:39:21,440 --> 01:39:23,790
<i>Please stop it.</i>

1022
01:39:25,240 --> 01:39:27,510
<i>Please go away.</i>

1023
01:39:28,600 --> 01:39:30,630
Go away, for God's sake!

1024
01:39:34,400 --> 01:39:37,670
You tell them I'll be staying.

1025
01:39:55,440 --> 01:39:57,950
Is there anybody here?

1026
01:40:05,520 --> 01:40:07,510
Where the hell is everybody?

1027
01:40:07,680 --> 01:40:09,670
(GIRL) Agh!

1028
01:40:10,600 --> 01:40:12,550
Agh!

1029
01:40:13,040 --> 01:40:15,870
Agh! Don't come near me!

1030
01:40:18,320 --> 01:40:22,830
Everybody's gone - the ones that could.

1031
01:40:24,480 --> 01:40:27,310
They didn't believe you were staying.

1032
01:40:28,120 --> 01:40:30,750
More of us like this.

1033
01:40:31,480 --> 01:40:33,990
They were frightened... Agh!

1034
01:40:34,160 --> 01:40:35,750
<i>Please...</i>

1035
01:40:37,600 --> 01:40:40,790
I'm not brave. I can't...

1036
01:40:43,280 --> 01:40:45,270
I can't wait.

1037
01:40:47,320 --> 01:40:50,710
Can you get me something to finish it?

1038
01:41:06,880 --> 01:41:10,270
(FLY BUZZES)

1039
01:41:55,000 --> 01:41:58,870
- No!
- It's no use to you, love. It's coffee.

1040
01:41:59,040 --> 01:42:04,160
Here. I've got some beans here.
There. And a can opener for you.

1041
01:42:06,040 --> 01:42:10,750
I want you to tell me if you've heard
of a girl around here, a girl who can see.

1042
01:42:10,920 --> 01:42:14,950
- She's probably leading a party of people.
- I was with them.

1043
01:42:15,120 --> 01:42:17,270
- Where?
- I lost them.

1044
01:42:17,440 --> 01:42:20,150
- Couldn't find them again.
- Whereabouts?

1045
01:42:20,320 --> 01:42:22,310
- Hotel.
- Which hotel?

1046
01:42:22,480 --> 01:42:26,550
- I don't know.
- You want to keep those, don't you?

1047
01:42:26,720 --> 01:42:30,950
- They're mine. You gave them to me.
- When you tell me about the hotel.

1048
01:42:31,120 --> 01:42:36,110
Was it large or small? Was the furniture good?
Were there steps? Did it have a big door?

1049
01:42:36,280 --> 01:42:39,470
A large hotel, I think. Large.

1050
01:42:39,640 --> 01:42:41,630
It sounded hollow.

1051
01:42:41,800 --> 01:42:44,390
<i>You know, escalators.</i>

1052
01:42:44,560 --> 01:42:47,750
<i>Thick carpets. Revolving doors.</i>

1053
01:43:07,000 --> 01:43:09,710
God, did I need that!

1054
01:43:25,320 --> 01:43:29,950
- What are you doing?
- I'm looking for a girl who can see.

1055
01:43:30,120 --> 01:43:32,950
She's tall, blonde.

1056
01:43:33,120 --> 01:43:35,500
She was leading a group of people.

1057
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:39,750
<i>- Is she here?
- Perhaps.</i>

1058
01:43:39,920 --> 01:43:43,670
- I've got to find her!
- It's too late.

1059
01:43:44,640 --> 01:43:47,310
If she isn't dead, she's gone.

1060
01:43:48,560 --> 01:43:50,860
They've all gone.

1061
01:44:14,520 --> 01:44:18,350
<i>(FOOTSTEPS)</i>

1062
01:44:22,200 --> 01:44:23,670
Jo?

1063
01:44:23,840 --> 01:44:27,110
<i>(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)</i>

1064
01:45:41,800 --> 01:45:44,360
I'm looking for a girl who can see.

1065
01:45:44,520 --> 01:45:47,430
She's tall, blonde.

1066
01:45:47,600 --> 01:45:50,590
She was leading a group of people.

1067
01:45:51,440 --> 01:45:54,030
<i>- Is she here?
- Perhaps.</i>

1068
01:45:54,920 --> 01:45:57,950
- I've got to find her!
- It's too late.

1069
01:46:12,120 --> 01:46:15,110
<i>(FOOTSTEPS)</i>

1070
01:46:20,200 --> 01:46:21,510
Jo?

1071
01:46:57,800 --> 01:47:00,870
<i>(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)</i>

1072
01:47:07,920 --> 01:47:10,480
What do you want?

1073
01:47:10,640 --> 01:47:13,870
Came to see if there was anyone still here.

1074
01:47:14,040 --> 01:47:17,030
You looking for more gang leaders?

1075
01:47:18,600 --> 01:47:23,390
As far as I can see,
there are no more gangs left to lead.

1076
01:47:23,560 --> 01:47:26,070
I came to make my peace.

1077
01:47:27,560 --> 01:47:29,830
To ask to join up.

1078
01:47:30,520 --> 01:47:33,150
Are yours all dead?

1079
01:47:34,600 --> 01:47:37,310
They will be by tomorrow.

1080
01:47:38,920 --> 01:47:40,830
Same with mine.

1081
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:43,350
They got it right.

1082
01:47:45,280 --> 01:47:50,790
We've got to start again.
The only question is, ''How?''

1083
01:47:54,280 --> 01:47:57,310
(BILL) I'm leaving first thing in the morning.

1084
01:48:10,560 --> 01:48:13,910
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

1085
01:48:45,800 --> 01:48:52,670
<i>(CONGREGATION)
# Oh, God our help in ages past</i>

1086
01:48:52,840 --> 01:48:58,110
# Our hope for years to come

1087
01:48:58,280 --> 01:49:05,070
# Be thou our guide while troubles last

1088
01:49:05,240 --> 01:49:11,580
# And our eternal home #

1089
01:49:13,320 --> 01:49:18,590
My friends, let us renew our thanks to God

1090
01:49:19,440 --> 01:49:23,190
for preserving us in the midst of such disaster.

1091
01:49:24,320 --> 01:49:28,510
I will ask you to pray
that he will look with compassion

1092
01:49:28,680 --> 01:49:32,790
on all those who still wander alone
in the darkness,

1093
01:49:33,960 --> 01:49:38,630
and that it will please him
to guide their feet hither

1094
01:49:38,800 --> 01:49:42,750
in order that we may succour them.

1095
01:49:44,360 --> 01:49:48,630
I'm sorry to keep you waiting,
but there's so much to do.

1096
01:49:48,800 --> 01:49:53,430
Miss Durrant, I'm looking for
the girl I was with at the university.

1097
01:49:53,600 --> 01:49:57,510
You may remember us together.
She was tall, blonde, about 23.

1098
01:49:57,680 --> 01:50:00,190
<i>- Her name was Payton.
- Miss Payton?</i>

1099
01:50:00,360 --> 01:50:05,110
No, I can't help you, I'm afraid.
She's certainly not here now.

1100
01:50:05,280 --> 01:50:08,470
She may have gone with the others.
I can't be sure.

1101
01:50:08,640 --> 01:50:12,230
- The others?
- Mr Beadley and Major Anderson.

1102
01:50:12,400 --> 01:50:15,990
- And the others at the university.
- They're not here?

1103
01:50:16,160 --> 01:50:20,390
They did come here. It was Mr Beadley
who knew of this house.

1104
01:50:20,560 --> 01:50:25,350
But a few of us disagreed with their ideas
as to the future of society.

1105
01:50:25,520 --> 01:50:29,270
Remember they gave us
an outline at the university?

1106
01:50:29,440 --> 01:50:30,830
I remember.

1107
01:50:31,000 --> 01:50:33,590
They believe the human race cannot survive

1108
01:50:33,760 --> 01:50:37,910
without the complete abolition of morality
as we've understood it.

1109
01:50:38,080 --> 01:50:41,590
That everything should be subservient
to the production of children,

1110
01:50:41,760 --> 01:50:45,790
and whether or not a child is a child
of true love is of no importance.

1111
01:50:45,960 --> 01:50:49,740
When they arrived, they repeated
that acceptance of their philosophy

1112
01:50:49,920 --> 01:50:53,150
was a precondition of membership.

1113
01:50:53,320 --> 01:50:56,990
We agreed to separate
and they volunteered to find somewhere else.

1114
01:50:57,160 --> 01:50:59,540
Those of us that remain are Christian.

1115
01:50:59,720 --> 01:51:02,790
We believe we must turn to Our Lord and say,

1116
01:51:02,960 --> 01:51:06,310
''We put our trust in you. Your laws are our laws.

1117
01:51:06,480 --> 01:51:10,790
''Guide us in your way
and we know that our souls will survive.''

1118
01:51:12,440 --> 01:51:15,590
(JACK) What are you going to do?
Are you moving on?

1119
01:51:18,640 --> 01:51:22,550
(BILL) I've got to find the other party,
see if Jo's with them.

1120
01:51:22,720 --> 01:51:25,950
I'd put more than I'd realised in her being here.

1121
01:51:26,120 --> 01:51:28,470
(JACK) Look, give it a day.

1122
01:51:29,800 --> 01:51:33,470
Let me see what the chances are
of getting this place together.

1123
01:51:33,640 --> 01:51:36,830
If it looks a possibility, I'll stay.

1124
01:51:38,200 --> 01:51:40,710
If not, I'll come with you.

1125
01:51:40,880 --> 01:51:46,150
- (BILL) Their intentions are good.
- Huh! So were mine in London.

1126
01:51:46,320 --> 01:51:49,590
Good intentions aren't enough any more.

1127
01:51:50,640 --> 01:51:55,190
This place could be a going concern,
if it's properly organised.

1128
01:51:55,360 --> 01:51:59,990
You've got good, well-protected land,
cattle, a fresh water supply.

1129
01:52:00,160 --> 01:52:04,270
You've even got an electricity generator,
which, by the way, I fixed.

1130
01:52:04,440 --> 01:52:07,110
It's about time somebody had.

1131
01:52:07,280 --> 01:52:09,710
You must build up your stocks from outside.

1132
01:52:09,880 --> 01:52:13,270
Get as much as you can
whilst it's still there to take.

1133
01:52:13,440 --> 01:52:16,350
It's not robbery. It's self-preservation.

1134
01:52:16,520 --> 01:52:20,990
I've already planned for the blind
to be taught to do useful work.

1135
01:52:21,160 --> 01:52:24,590
Your vicar wanted them to learn basket weaving!

1136
01:52:24,760 --> 01:52:29,470
You mustn't let him persuade you
to bring any more blind people here.

1137
01:52:29,640 --> 01:52:34,150
You can just about cope with what you have.
Any more and you've had it.

1138
01:52:34,320 --> 01:52:40,470
If you don't all starve to death,
the ones who can see will have breakdowns.

1139
01:52:40,640 --> 01:52:43,790
This is not speculation. This is predicted fact!

1140
01:52:45,800 --> 01:52:50,190
On the other hand, if we do as I say...

1141
01:52:58,640 --> 01:53:00,710
You did your best!

1142
01:53:02,920 --> 01:53:04,550
Let's go.

1143
01:54:00,560 --> 01:54:03,950
- Ready to take five?
- Cheers.

1144
01:54:39,320 --> 01:54:41,700
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

1145
01:56:00,520 --> 01:56:02,390
(BILL) Don't move! Get back!

1146
01:56:29,680 --> 01:56:32,060
(BILL) There's no one else here.

1147
01:56:33,440 --> 01:56:36,270
(JACK) It's almost as if it was waiting for him.

1148
01:56:37,200 --> 01:56:40,980
As if it knew he was
going to come out of that door.

1149
01:56:43,560 --> 01:56:48,710
Come on. You know all about these things.
You've worked with them.

1150
01:56:48,880 --> 01:56:51,110
Yes, all right.

1151
01:56:51,280 --> 01:56:55,470
They make me sick. They're like maggots
or vultures. I was ready for that.

1152
01:56:55,640 --> 01:56:58,790
But there's more and more all the time!

1153
01:57:00,280 --> 01:57:05,270
They seem to know where we are. They turned
towards us when they saw the lorries.

1154
01:57:05,440 --> 01:57:08,270
Some even moved towards us.

1155
01:57:08,440 --> 01:57:12,670
They didn't see the lorries.
They're plants. They can't see.

1156
01:57:20,120 --> 01:57:23,430
The trouble with triffids is what we don't know.

1157
01:57:24,200 --> 01:57:28,630
Some scientists bred a very special plant
to produce a very special oil.

1158
01:57:28,800 --> 01:57:32,190
We got the special oil
and we're lumbered with a special plant.

1159
01:57:32,360 --> 01:57:34,740
- Has it got a brain?
- It's a plant!

1160
01:57:34,920 --> 01:57:37,870
- That's no answer.
- That's all I know!

1161
01:57:41,880 --> 01:57:45,660
- Do they frighten you?
- Yes, and they sicken me, too.

1162
01:57:45,840 --> 01:57:48,430
What sickens me most is inside this mess

1163
01:57:48,600 --> 01:57:52,670
they are the only things
that are gonna fatten and thrive.

1164
01:57:54,560 --> 01:57:57,230
I'm going back to Tynsham.

1165
01:57:59,040 --> 01:58:02,230
No, it's not a snap decision.

1166
01:58:02,400 --> 01:58:07,630
It's been growing all day,
driving through the desolation out there.

1167
01:58:07,800 --> 01:58:12,630
Village after village, house after house.
Not a breath of human life anywhere.

1168
01:58:13,520 --> 01:58:18,590
I've felt more lonely in these last few days
than I thought it possible.

1169
01:58:18,760 --> 01:58:23,700
So...there's one reason - my human need.

1170
01:58:23,880 --> 01:58:26,180
But the main reason is this.

1171
01:58:26,360 --> 01:58:29,670
I've been working this out on the road.

1172
01:58:29,840 --> 01:58:34,830
We must be part of a community
to have any hope for the future at all.

1173
01:58:35,000 --> 01:58:39,630
At the moment we've got all we need.
Food, supplies, everything.

1174
01:58:40,720 --> 01:58:43,870
But the food will go bad, the metal will rust,

1175
01:58:44,040 --> 01:58:46,790
the petrol to drive the machines will run out.

1176
01:58:48,440 --> 01:58:50,550
Before that happens,

1177
01:58:50,720 --> 01:58:56,190
we have to learn to plough
and learn to make ploughs,

1178
01:58:56,360 --> 01:59:00,310
and learn to smelt the iron
to make the ploughshares.

1179
01:59:00,480 --> 01:59:04,710
We must learn to make good
all that we wear out. If not...

1180
01:59:04,880 --> 01:59:10,350
we say goodbye to civilisation
and we slide right back into savagery.

1181
01:59:14,520 --> 01:59:18,030
All the knowledge is there in books

1182
01:59:18,200 --> 01:59:20,870
if only we take the time to learn.

1183
01:59:21,040 --> 01:59:24,230
Time, you see. Time.

1184
01:59:27,200 --> 01:59:32,110
We need a community large enough
for some people to be free from production

1185
01:59:32,280 --> 01:59:35,310
to have time to study and experiment

1186
01:59:35,480 --> 01:59:40,470
and teach the kids to prepare for the day
when what we have is gone.

1187
01:59:40,640 --> 01:59:46,070
- What did you do before all this happened?
- I taught history...very badly.

1188
01:59:46,240 --> 01:59:49,110
But I'm talking sense now.

1189
01:59:50,000 --> 01:59:51,990
Yeah, I know.

1190
01:59:54,680 --> 01:59:59,430
I'll get my way at Tynsham.
I'll have to use more subtlety.

1191
02:00:00,960 --> 02:00:04,950
- But Ma Durrant needs us.
- I'm not going with you.

1192
02:00:06,320 --> 02:00:08,470
Why not?

1193
02:00:09,600 --> 02:00:11,590
I've got to find Jo.

1194
02:00:13,000 --> 02:00:16,190
You don't even know if she's still alive.

1195
02:00:16,360 --> 02:00:18,470
Quite right.

1196
02:00:19,400 --> 02:00:25,230
But I'm gonna find out. I'm gonna find that other
group. If she's not with them, I'll start again.

1197
02:00:25,400 --> 02:00:27,550
I'll start in the south and work...

1198
02:00:27,720 --> 02:00:30,310
- What?
- The south.

1199
02:00:30,480 --> 02:00:32,470
South Downs!

1200
02:00:33,320 --> 02:00:35,750
<i>A farmhouse overlooking Pulborough.</i>

1201
02:00:37,560 --> 02:00:40,830
We talked about it once as a place to go.

1202
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:44,620
- You've cracked it, then?
- If I can find it and if she's there.

1203
02:00:50,160 --> 02:00:54,190
When you find her,
bring her straight back to Tynsham.

1204
02:00:55,600 --> 02:00:59,550
I shall need your help
to make that woman see sense.

1205
02:01:35,560 --> 02:01:37,790
What the hell do you think you're doing?

1206
02:01:37,960 --> 02:01:40,870
<i>Please. Please come and see
what's happened to Tommy.</i>

1207
02:02:02,480 --> 02:02:06,870
A thing hit him and he fell down.
It wanted to hit me when I tried to help.

1208
02:02:07,040 --> 02:02:10,310
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

1209
02:02:10,480 --> 02:02:12,990
Get behind the wall, quickly!

1210
02:02:52,600 --> 02:02:55,670
<i>- (GIRL) Where are we going?
- (BILL) To find a lady.</i>

1211
02:02:55,840 --> 02:02:59,070
<i>- Is she nice?
- Yeah, I think so.</i>

1212
02:02:59,240 --> 02:03:01,470
<i>- (BILL) What's your name?
- Susan.</i>

1213
02:03:01,640 --> 02:03:04,510
<i>- I'm Bill.
- Thank you for letting me bring Rufus.</i>

1214
02:03:04,680 --> 02:03:08,110
<i>- He'll be very good.
- He'd better beI</i>

1215
02:04:09,680 --> 02:04:13,830
It's round here somewhere,
but I don't know quite where.

1216
02:04:14,000 --> 02:04:19,430
- What are you going to do?
- Wait till it's dark, then we'll try our lights.

1217
02:05:06,440 --> 02:05:09,630
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

1218
02:05:20,400 --> 02:05:22,780
Bill! Bill! There's a light!

1219
02:05:25,920 --> 02:05:28,550
I think there's a light.

1220
02:06:08,680 --> 02:06:11,240
Shall we go?

1221
02:06:21,320 --> 02:06:24,110
I've lost it. I've lost it!

1222
02:06:29,760 --> 02:06:31,750
Over there!

1223
02:06:39,320 --> 02:06:40,630
(BILL) Damn!

1224
02:06:42,480 --> 02:06:44,860
We'll have to go back.

1225
02:07:04,800 --> 02:07:06,990
There! There!

1226
02:07:31,680 --> 02:07:35,950
Hello, Bill. You've been a long time.

1227
02:07:49,760 --> 02:07:52,750
Hey! Can't you kiss her indoors?

1228
02:07:54,680 --> 02:08:00,470
<i>(JO ) Perhaps I should have woken
Dennis and Mary, but I didn't see much point.</i>

1229
02:08:02,000 --> 02:08:05,030
You'll meet them in the morning.

1230
02:08:06,040 --> 02:08:09,580
There were two other blind people staying here.

1231
02:08:09,760 --> 02:08:13,790
But they went out to get help
and never came back.

1232
02:08:13,960 --> 02:08:17,070
- Triffids?
- I expect so.

1233
02:08:17,240 --> 02:08:21,310
- Are there many round here?
- Far too many.

1234
02:08:21,480 --> 02:08:24,150
Is everything very black?

1235
02:08:25,040 --> 02:08:26,430
No.

1236
02:08:27,680 --> 02:08:32,470
We know we're here, there's Beadley's group
and people at Tynsham.

1237
02:08:32,640 --> 02:08:36,390
There must be similar groups all over the world.

1238
02:08:36,560 --> 02:08:41,830
It's gonna be a hell of a struggle,
but I think we might come through it.

1239
02:08:42,000 --> 02:08:46,270
I think we all better go to Tynsham
as soon as we can.

1240
02:08:46,960 --> 02:08:52,950
Coker said that the only way to survive
is to be part of a sizeable community.

1241
02:08:53,120 --> 02:08:55,420
I'm sure he's right.

1242
02:08:56,600 --> 02:08:59,630
We'll have to wait until Mary's baby's born.

1243
02:08:59,800 --> 02:09:02,790
It's due in a couple of weeks.

1244
02:09:02,960 --> 02:09:07,750
Well, there's no hurry. This place will do for a bit.

1245
02:09:10,400 --> 02:09:14,550
I'll drive to Tynsham in a few days,
tell them to be expecting us.

1246
02:10:08,120 --> 02:10:10,580
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

1247
02:10:51,520 --> 02:10:57,390
- (BILL) The others must have gone.
- But surely they must have left a message.

1248
02:10:57,560 --> 02:11:00,750
- I couldn't find one.
- What happened?

1249
02:11:02,440 --> 02:11:05,470
The disease. You could smell it.

1250
02:11:05,640 --> 02:11:09,630
There were bodies everywhere,
including Miss Durrant's.

1251
02:11:09,800 --> 02:11:13,110
- What about Coker?
- I dunno.

1252
02:11:14,280 --> 02:11:16,660
There were six new graves outside.

1253
02:11:18,280 --> 02:11:22,270
- We're on our own, then.
- We've got to try and make a go of it here.

1254
02:11:24,000 --> 02:11:26,380
(BILL) We will.

1255
02:14:39,900 --> 02:14:42,650
Where have you been? I've been worried stiff.

1256
02:14:42,820 --> 02:14:47,730
I had to change wheels three times
and take a 40-mile detour.

1257
02:14:47,900 --> 02:14:50,650
- Are the roads worse?
- Terrible.

1258
02:14:50,820 --> 02:14:54,730
- I won't get through much longer.
- Did you get my jeans?

1259
02:14:54,900 --> 02:15:00,020
- Did you get Susan's jeans?
- A dozen pairs. I hope you stop growing!

1260
02:15:00,180 --> 02:15:03,410
- Is David asleep?
- Of course he's not.

1261
02:15:04,140 --> 02:15:07,650
- Good night, Dad.
- You close your eyes.

1262
02:15:07,820 --> 02:15:10,610
<i>My fault. Pleasant dreams, son.</i>

1263
02:15:10,780 --> 02:15:14,320
- Good night, Uncle Bill.
- Good night, Alice.

1264
02:15:14,500 --> 02:15:18,370
(MARY) It's time you were asleep,
so put that candle out.

1265
02:15:18,540 --> 02:15:20,570
Sorry, Mummy.

1266
02:15:22,620 --> 02:15:28,050
- How did you know it was on?
- I guessed. Supper's ready, Bill.

1267
02:15:36,900 --> 02:15:39,890
Mmm. Good pickings. Good pickings.

1268
02:15:40,060 --> 02:15:42,810
It was a good trip
from the store's point of view.

1269
02:15:42,980 --> 02:15:46,890
I got nearly everything we wanted,
including the new Braille books.

1270
02:15:47,060 --> 02:15:50,010
- How's London looking?
- Greener and greener.

1271
02:15:50,180 --> 02:15:54,810
- I suppose the parks have gone wild?
- They've taken over some streets.

1272
02:15:54,980 --> 02:15:56,970
- (JO ) Must be eerie.
- It is.

1273
02:15:57,140 --> 02:16:00,330
- Are there any signs of life?
- A few cats and dogs.

1274
02:16:00,500 --> 02:16:04,890
Triffids, of course. I'm pretty certain
other people go raiding there.

1275
02:16:05,060 --> 02:16:09,010
There's indications of that,
but I didn't see anybody.

1276
02:16:09,180 --> 02:16:13,330
- I think it's my last visit, too.
- Why?

1277
02:16:14,460 --> 02:16:18,610
I was cruising down Tottenham Court Road
and a building collapsed.

1278
02:16:18,780 --> 02:16:20,290
Oh, my God!

1279
02:16:20,460 --> 02:16:24,210
It was ready to go. The vibration
of the Land Rover did the rest.

1280
02:16:24,380 --> 02:16:29,970
From now on, it'll have to be smaller towns.
We'll get what we need in a hand-barrow.

1281
02:16:30,140 --> 02:16:33,170
- Did you find another flame-thrower?
- I got two.

1282
02:16:33,340 --> 02:16:37,120
Not much of the fuel, though.
There's not much of that anywhere.

1283
02:16:37,300 --> 02:16:41,770
- What was the triffid count this morning?
- Over a thousand.

1284
02:16:41,940 --> 02:16:45,250
But it's only ten days
since you wiped them all out.

1285
02:16:45,420 --> 02:16:49,650
- Did you see many between here and London?
- Not in these numbers.

1286
02:16:49,820 --> 02:16:51,610
- You suggest we move?
- No.

1287
02:16:51,780 --> 02:16:56,170
We've got a good place, a place we know.
You need that when you can't see.

1288
02:16:56,340 --> 02:16:59,880
You built a fence. They're on the outside,
we're on the in.

1289
02:17:00,060 --> 02:17:02,890
If you burn them off, there's no real problem.

1290
02:17:03,060 --> 02:17:06,050
No. No, I shouldn't think so.

1291
02:17:06,220 --> 02:17:10,130
(BIRD SONG)

1292
02:17:26,780 --> 02:17:29,770
<i>(GENTLE TAPPING)</i>

1293
02:17:41,780 --> 02:17:43,330
Aagh!

1294
02:17:53,340 --> 02:17:56,610
- Jo? Jo?
- They've broken through the fence!

1295
02:17:56,780 --> 02:17:59,240
<i>- MummyI
- David!</i>

1296
02:17:59,420 --> 02:18:00,730
<i>MummyI</i>

1297
02:18:00,900 --> 02:18:03,610
<i>(WHIPLASH SOUND )</i>

1298
02:18:05,220 --> 02:18:06,850
Wait!

1299
02:18:07,020 --> 02:18:09,610
Stay there! Don't move!

1300
02:18:33,980 --> 02:18:35,890
We won.

1301
02:18:37,340 --> 02:18:39,090
Yeah.

1302
02:18:52,980 --> 02:18:55,850
Are you sure this is safe?

1303
02:18:56,740 --> 02:19:02,770
I doubt if triffids can walk on shingle.
They'd make a hell of a noise.

1304
02:19:07,260 --> 02:19:10,880
It's so marvellous
to get out of the compound!

1305
02:19:13,340 --> 02:19:15,800
Oh! Look at the gulls!

1306
02:19:18,060 --> 02:19:21,810
To watch them, you could almost think
nothing had ever happened.

1307
02:19:21,980 --> 02:19:26,650
There are more of them this year.
I'm glad about that.

1308
02:19:27,940 --> 02:19:31,130
Are our chances getting better?

1309
02:19:32,900 --> 02:19:36,850
If it weren't for the triffids,
I'd say we had a very good chance.

1310
02:19:37,020 --> 02:19:41,210
There hasn't been a single break-in
since we electrified the fence.

1311
02:19:41,380 --> 02:19:45,450
If we kept the generator running all the time,
the fence would be wonderful,

1312
02:19:45,620 --> 02:19:49,050
but you know we can't get enough fuel.

1313
02:19:49,220 --> 02:19:52,490
But I thought we'd found the answer to that.

1314
02:19:52,660 --> 02:19:56,890
Turn it on for a few minutes
at a different time each day.

1315
02:19:57,060 --> 02:20:03,160
Susan says they'll work it out.
She says they can hear the generator.

1316
02:20:04,500 --> 02:20:08,090
Sometimes I think they do have intelligence.

1317
02:20:08,260 --> 02:20:13,200
They know their purpose is to get us.
And sooner or later they will.

1318
02:20:13,380 --> 02:20:17,080
No! Look, we're gonna beat them. We've got to.

1319
02:20:17,260 --> 02:20:23,050
I don't want our children living in a reservation
spending all their time keeping triffids out.

1320
02:20:23,220 --> 02:20:27,970
Oh, God, I'm sorry. Here I am being depressing

1321
02:20:28,140 --> 02:20:33,450
when it's the first time we've paused
from the business of keeping alive.

1322
02:20:33,620 --> 02:20:36,000
And I am alive.

1323
02:20:36,180 --> 02:20:38,890
More than I've ever been.

1324
02:20:40,700 --> 02:20:43,080
And I'm happier, too.

1325
02:20:56,220 --> 02:20:58,330
I'm sorry about the weather.

1326
02:21:08,860 --> 02:21:11,290
What are we going to tell the children?

1327
02:21:12,220 --> 02:21:17,290
Sooner or later they're going to want to know
why all this has happened.

1328
02:21:17,460 --> 02:21:21,610
Do we tell them that the world
was wonderfully clever

1329
02:21:21,780 --> 02:21:24,890
but so very wicked it had to be destroyed?

1330
02:21:26,060 --> 02:21:29,170
Or do we tell them it destroyed itself by accident?

1331
02:21:32,260 --> 02:21:34,850
We tell them the truth.

1332
02:21:35,020 --> 02:21:37,480
We destroyed it.

1333
02:21:38,820 --> 02:21:43,050
- We created the triffids.
- We didn't create the comet.

1334
02:21:44,900 --> 02:21:46,690
Was it a comet?

1335
02:21:48,300 --> 02:21:50,290
What do you mean?

1336
02:21:52,380 --> 02:21:56,450
Do you know how many satellites
were going round up there?

1337
02:21:56,620 --> 02:22:00,770
How many weapons?
Or what was in the weapons?

1338
02:22:01,780 --> 02:22:04,050
They never told us.

1339
02:22:04,220 --> 02:22:06,520
They never asked us.

1340
02:22:07,540 --> 02:22:11,930
I suppose one of these weapons
had been specially constructed

1341
02:22:12,100 --> 02:22:15,720
to emit a radiation that our eyes couldn't stand.

1342
02:22:15,900 --> 02:22:18,570
Something that would burn out the optic nerve.

1343
02:22:18,740 --> 02:22:22,930
- That couldn't blind the whole world.
- Suppose there was an accident.

1344
02:22:23,940 --> 02:22:29,410
This weapon would operate at low levels,
only blinding people they wanted to blind.

1345
02:22:29,580 --> 02:22:33,010
But after the accident, it went off so far up

1346
02:22:33,180 --> 02:22:37,530
that anyone on earth could receive
direct radiation from it.

1347
02:22:38,620 --> 02:22:43,370
What about the mysterious disease?
Where did that come from?

1348
02:22:47,260 --> 02:22:51,330
We were walking on a tightrope
for a hell of a long time.

1349
02:22:51,500 --> 02:22:54,650
Sooner or later, a foot had to slip.

1350
02:22:57,620 --> 02:22:59,970
Well, if that's right,

1351
02:23:01,060 --> 02:23:05,090
it means our children can't make
a worse mess of it than we did.

1352
02:23:05,260 --> 02:23:07,970
And that's cheering for them.

1353
02:23:08,700 --> 02:23:10,290
Yes, it is.

1354
02:23:28,420 --> 02:23:30,850
(JO ) Oh, my God! The farm!

1355
02:23:46,140 --> 02:23:50,290
- What's going on?
- I had to burn it to signal them.

1356
02:23:54,180 --> 02:23:55,610
(BILL) Jack?

1357
02:23:55,780 --> 02:23:59,650
- Hello, Bill!
- Jack! My God! I thought you were dead!

1358
02:23:59,820 --> 02:24:03,130
- Who, me? Not yet!
- Jo, this is Jack Coker.

1359
02:24:03,300 --> 02:24:07,530
- We have met. I was his prisoner.
- It's a little late for me to apologise.

1360
02:24:07,700 --> 02:24:12,210
It's great to see you. It's six years
since we've seen another human being.

1361
02:24:12,380 --> 02:24:15,450
Sit down. Tell me what happened to you.

1362
02:24:15,620 --> 02:24:19,090
- I went to Tynsham to look for you.
- The disease hit us.

1363
02:24:19,260 --> 02:24:23,770
- Yes. I found Miss Durrant's body.
- She stayed to nurse the sick.

1364
02:24:23,940 --> 02:24:28,290
I admired her, but those who can survive must.
I took the healthy ones away.

1365
02:24:28,460 --> 02:24:31,090
So where's the helicopter from?

1366
02:24:31,260 --> 02:24:35,040
- Did you know we were here?
- I knew where to look.

1367
02:24:35,220 --> 02:24:39,770
We're on the Isle of Wight. That's
my third helicopter. I smashed the others up!

1368
02:24:39,940 --> 02:24:44,010
- Well, you try learning to fly from a book.
- (LAUGHTER)

1369
02:24:44,180 --> 02:24:47,210
We're getting things organised over there now.

1370
02:24:47,380 --> 02:24:50,370
An island is the only defence against triffids.

1371
02:24:50,540 --> 02:24:54,240
- There are no triffids there?
- They were there.

1372
02:24:54,420 --> 02:24:58,410
We moved into a large house.
They congregated in thousands.

1373
02:24:58,580 --> 02:25:01,250
We wiped them out with flame-throwers.
More came.

1374
02:25:01,420 --> 02:25:03,610
We must have wiped out 50,000 at least.

1375
02:25:03,780 --> 02:25:09,330
Then, when they didn't come any more,
we hunted them down and destroyed them.

1376
02:25:09,500 --> 02:25:15,370
The seeds still blow across,
but we have a hunt for those every spring.

1377
02:25:15,540 --> 02:25:20,010
- That's wonderful.
- (JO ) Are there other inhabited places?

1378
02:25:20,180 --> 02:25:23,490
I've come across several since I've been flying.

1379
02:25:23,660 --> 02:25:28,650
I ask if they want to join us. Some do, some
don't - those who don't want to be governed.

1380
02:25:28,820 --> 02:25:34,570
A large group in Brighton shot at the helicopter,
so I left them to stew.

1381
02:25:35,300 --> 02:25:38,490
There's several hundred of us now -
who can see, I mean,

1382
02:25:38,660 --> 02:25:40,690
and a good few blind as well.

1383
02:25:40,860 --> 02:25:43,420
What we need is you.

1384
02:25:43,580 --> 02:25:45,330
Me?

1385
02:25:46,380 --> 02:25:50,730
We can keep the triffids away from the island,
but that's not enough.

1386
02:25:50,900 --> 02:25:55,650
We've got to find a selective killer to finish them.
That means research.

1387
02:25:55,820 --> 02:26:01,090
You were a biologist on a triffid farm.
We can give you facilities, help.

1388
02:26:01,260 --> 02:26:04,850
We need your experience and skill.
Are you interested?

1389
02:26:05,020 --> 02:26:06,810
- Yes, very!
- Good.

1390
02:26:06,980 --> 02:26:11,840
- If Bill goes, we all go.
- Of course. One thing I should make clear.

1391
02:26:12,020 --> 02:26:17,770
We have all agreed we're...we're not out
to reconstruct the world as it was.

1392
02:26:17,940 --> 02:26:21,250
We want to build something new, better.

1393
02:26:21,420 --> 02:26:25,570
Some people don't agree with that.
They want to keep the old features.

1394
02:26:25,740 --> 02:26:29,690
If anybody doesn't like us,
we ask them to move somewhere else.

1395
02:26:29,860 --> 02:26:33,370
''Somewhere else'' sounds like a poor offer.

1396
02:26:33,540 --> 02:26:37,650
I don't mean we throw them back to the triffids.

1397
02:26:37,820 --> 02:26:42,090
One group did move to the Channel Islands.
I believe they're doing well.

1398
02:26:42,260 --> 02:26:47,410
Anyway, the best way to learn about us
is to come and find out for yourselves.

1399
02:26:47,580 --> 02:26:51,330
I'm sure we will take to each other,
but if we don't,

1400
02:26:51,500 --> 02:26:55,570
you'll find the Channel Islands is better than this
a few years from now.

1401
02:27:15,540 --> 02:27:18,130
(BILL) Isn't it what we've been waiting for?

1402
02:27:18,300 --> 02:27:19,890
(JO ) I know.

1403
02:27:21,100 --> 02:27:25,690
We must beat the triffids.
We can't do it here. We must go.

1404
02:27:25,860 --> 02:27:30,010
Bill, couldn't we have one more summer here?

1405
02:27:30,180 --> 02:27:34,610
One more summer without any worry
'cause we know we've got somewhere to go.

1406
02:27:34,780 --> 02:27:37,240
One marvellous summer.

1407
02:27:37,420 --> 02:27:41,610
I suggest we go the first day of autumn.

1408
02:27:48,620 --> 02:27:51,210
(FLIES BUZZ)

1409
02:27:55,980 --> 02:27:59,570
# We all live in a yellow submarine

1410
02:27:59,740 --> 02:28:03,250
# A yellow submarine, a yellow submarine

1411
02:28:03,420 --> 02:28:06,810
# And our friends are all aboard

1412
02:28:06,980 --> 02:28:10,970
# Many more of them live next door... #

1413
02:28:47,700 --> 02:28:51,770
My name's Torrence.
I'm Commander, South-East region.

1414
02:28:51,940 --> 02:28:57,490
I'm Chief Executive Officer
of the Emergency Council for the South-East.

1415
02:28:57,660 --> 02:29:04,050
As such, I supervise the distribution
and allocation of personnel.

1416
02:29:05,180 --> 02:29:08,650
I'm sorry, but I've never heard of this council.

1417
02:29:08,820 --> 02:29:13,370
We were equally ignorant of your group
until we saw your fire yesterday.

1418
02:29:13,540 --> 02:29:15,920
When such a group is discovered,

1419
02:29:16,100 --> 02:29:19,330
it's my job to investigate it
and make adjustments.

1420
02:29:19,500 --> 02:29:21,850
It's a good place you've taken over.

1421
02:29:22,020 --> 02:29:25,770
- It belongs to Mr Brent.
- We can leave Mr Brent out of it.

1422
02:29:25,940 --> 02:29:29,450
He's only here now because you made it possible.

1423
02:29:29,620 --> 02:29:34,130
The society which gave sanction
to his ownership no longer exists.

1424
02:29:34,300 --> 02:29:38,850
Mr Brent is not sighted
and so is not competent to hold authority.

1425
02:29:39,020 --> 02:29:42,450
There are seven of you,
all sighted except these two.

1426
02:29:42,620 --> 02:29:44,330
Yes.

1427
02:29:44,500 --> 02:29:49,570
That's quite disproportionate, I'm afraid.
We have to be realistic these days.

1428
02:29:54,460 --> 02:29:59,610
I'd better put you in the picture.
Regional headquarters is in Brighton.

1429
02:29:59,780 --> 02:30:04,290
We survived the sickness
and we had plenty of stores.

1430
02:30:04,460 --> 02:30:07,090
Later on we conveyed them from other places.

1431
02:30:07,260 --> 02:30:10,930
But the roads are getting too bad for lorries now.

1432
02:30:11,100 --> 02:30:16,730
So we've got to disperse and live off the land.
To do this, we've got to break into smaller units.

1433
02:30:16,900 --> 02:30:22,090
The unit has been fixed at one sighted person
to ten blind, plus children.

1434
02:30:22,260 --> 02:30:26,850
We shall allocate you 18 more blind persons,
making 20 with the two you have here.

1435
02:30:27,020 --> 02:30:32,140
20? This land won't support 20 people.
It's enough just to feed ourselves.

1436
02:30:32,300 --> 02:30:36,490
It's perfectly possible. I'm offering you
command of the double unit here.

1437
02:30:36,660 --> 02:30:40,530
If you don't take it, we shall get someone else in.

1438
02:30:40,700 --> 02:30:44,970
- Look at the place! It can't be done.
- It can be done.

1439
02:30:45,140 --> 02:30:48,450
Of course, you'll have to lower
your standards a bit.

1440
02:30:48,620 --> 02:30:52,010
For the first six or seven years it'll be hard work.

1441
02:30:52,180 --> 02:30:57,090
But after that, you'll be able to relax
until you're simply supervising.

1442
02:30:57,260 --> 02:31:02,690
You'll be head of a clan and you'll have
an inheritance to hand on to your sons.

1443
02:31:04,740 --> 02:31:07,570
Do I understand that...

1444
02:31:08,660 --> 02:31:12,250
you're offering to make me a kind of feudal lord?

1445
02:31:12,420 --> 02:31:14,980
That's a very good parallel in many ways.

1446
02:31:15,140 --> 02:31:20,080
It's the obvious social and economic structure
for the state of things we're facing now.

1447
02:31:20,260 --> 02:31:26,770
<i>Yes. I don't quite see. Perhaps you could explain
where you and your council stand in all this?</i>

1448
02:31:26,940 --> 02:31:30,810
Supreme authority is vested
in the council. It will rule.

1449
02:31:30,980 --> 02:31:34,810
- It will also control the armed forces.
- Armed forces?

1450
02:31:34,980 --> 02:31:38,760
Then, of course,
there's the rest of the world to consider.

1451
02:31:38,940 --> 02:31:41,850
Everywhere must be in the same sort of chaos.

1452
02:31:42,020 --> 02:31:45,970
It's our national duty to assume a dominant role

1453
02:31:46,140 --> 02:31:48,370
and discourage any aggressors.

1454
02:31:48,540 --> 02:31:55,050
- God almighty! He wants to start a war.
- ''War'' is an unjustifiable exaggeration.

1455
02:31:55,220 --> 02:31:58,530
It will simply be a matter of pacifying the tribes

1456
02:31:58,700 --> 02:32:02,370
that have reverted to primitive lawlessness.

1457
02:32:04,540 --> 02:32:07,730
To come back to the matter of allocation.

1458
02:32:07,900 --> 02:32:13,410
You have three sighted adults here.
Your 20 blind people only rate two.

1459
02:32:13,580 --> 02:32:15,730
The girl can come to headquarters.

1460
02:32:15,900 --> 02:32:20,530
We shall find suitable work
until she's old enough to take charge of a unit.

1461
02:32:20,700 --> 02:32:26,610
Er... My wife and I regard Susan as our daughter.

1462
02:32:26,780 --> 02:32:29,530
I'm sorry. Those are the regulations.

1463
02:32:29,700 --> 02:32:32,260
I am empowered to enforce them.

1464
02:32:32,420 --> 02:32:36,530
We'd require guarantees
and undertakings as to Susan's future.

1465
02:32:36,700 --> 02:32:41,290
Naturally, we shall offer you
all possible assurances.

1466
02:32:41,460 --> 02:32:45,240
I trust you'll be our guests for tonight.

1467
02:32:46,300 --> 02:32:49,570
Give us a chance to get to know each other, eh?

1468
02:32:51,260 --> 02:32:52,850
You're very kind.

1469
02:32:55,660 --> 02:32:58,810
(RAUCOUS LAUGHTER)

1470
02:32:58,980 --> 02:33:00,770
Susan.

1471
02:33:04,660 --> 02:33:08,170
They're not going to take you anywhere.

1472
02:33:08,340 --> 02:33:12,090
Not after the treat we've planned for them tonight.

1473
02:33:15,980 --> 02:33:18,130
(LAUGHTER WITHIN)

1474
02:33:20,140 --> 02:33:25,160
If you'd ordered this in a restaurant,
you'd have fainted when you got the bill.

1475
02:33:25,340 --> 02:33:27,610
I liberated it.

1476
02:33:27,780 --> 02:33:31,770
- Let's liberate another.
- No, we can't take all your best.

1477
02:33:31,940 --> 02:33:35,720
Nonsense! You can't take it with you.
And if you can, you're not going to!

1478
02:33:36,980 --> 02:33:39,850
<i>(BILL) I'll pop into the cellar, get another one.</i>

1479
02:33:40,020 --> 02:33:44,770
<i>(JO ) You must try my mead later.
It's guaranteed to fell an ox.</i>

1480
02:34:23,260 --> 02:34:25,370
Steady on.

1481
02:34:25,540 --> 02:34:28,770
Fell an ox? It'd fell a whole load of elephants!

1482
02:34:30,500 --> 02:34:32,170
Now, what was I saying?

1483
02:34:32,340 --> 02:34:35,050
Oh, God, I've forgotten again.

1484
02:34:37,860 --> 02:34:41,090
<i>(BILL) We haven't had such an evening
since we came here.</i>

1485
02:34:41,260 --> 02:34:45,850
<i>(TORRENCE) Wonderful evening.
I shall sleep like a baby tonight.</i>

1486
02:35:16,620 --> 02:35:18,610
(DAVID ) Mummy...
(BILL) Shh!

1487
02:36:23,780 --> 02:36:26,970
<i>(TAPPING)</i>

1488
02:36:50,180 --> 02:36:52,610
Everybody keep down low.

1489
02:37:13,940 --> 02:37:15,570
(GUNSHOTS)

1490
02:37:25,540 --> 02:37:28,650
Amazing what honey will do.

1491
02:37:42,820 --> 02:37:45,250
- Isle of Wight?
- Yes!

1492
02:37:46,340 --> 02:37:50,890
- Sorry you couldn't end the summer here.
- We'll come back one day.

1493
02:37:54,540 --> 02:37:57,930
<i>(BILL) Shall we ever be able to come back?</i>

1494
02:37:58,100 --> 02:38:02,130
<i>Oh, yes, we shall. We'll work and we'll learn.</i>

1495
02:38:02,300 --> 02:38:07,890
<i>And then we, or our children, will come back
and drive every triffid from this land.</i>

1496
